<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Agrees to Spending to Crack Down Teen Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday
agreed to the Clinton administration's request for 34 million
dollars to pay for a nation-wide crackdown on illegal sales of
tobacco products to youths under age 18.
</P>
<P>
In July, the Senate approved only 4.9 million dollars for the
Food and Drug Administration (FDA) program, but on a voice vote
agreed to an amendment to the agriculture spending bill adding 29
million dollars. An effort to kill the amendment failed by a 28-70
vote.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the House of Representatives has approved 24 million
dollars for the FDA program. Differences between the House and
Senate spending bills have to be resolved in a conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore told senators in a letter made public on
Tuesday that the FDA needs the full amount requested if all 50
states are to check whether stores are complying with new rules
requiring identification checks tobacco buyers.
</P>
<P>
More than one billion dollars worth of tobacco products are
illegally sold to minors each year, Gore said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
