<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Continue Cautious Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
maintain its cautious fiscal and monetary policies and the
relaxing liquidity will be continued in stages, Finance Minister
Mar'ie Muhammad said today.
</P>
<P>
"The interest rate will be decreased in stages in line with the
situation," the minister told the press when announcing the
results of a limited cabinet meeting on economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's revenues will fall significantly due to
excessive rupiah fluctuation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attacks following the de factor
devaluation of the Thai baht and the Philippine peso in July.
</P>
<P>
The value of the rupiah has dropped more than 22 percent in the
past eight months, far higher than the 5 to 6 percent planned by
the government for each year.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the rupiah devaluation, "some of the projects
financed by the state budget might be canceled or rescheduled as a
consequence of the reduced state budget," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He also said the present monetary crisis in several countries
indicates that the banking sector has an important role in
improving or worsening the situation.
</P>
<P>
Despite the sharp devaluation of the rupiah, the government did
not sacrifice its foreign exchange, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bank Indonesia (central bank) Governor Soedradjad
said the country's foreign exchange reserve at present stands at
20.3 billion U.S. dollars, excluding a two billion U.S. dollars
stand-by loan.
</P>
<P>
Asked when the government will raise the interest of short term
certificates of Bank Indonesia (SBI) and when would trading of
securities be carried out, he said they would depend on the latest
developments.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie also said that the situation in the country's capital
market as well as those in other Southeast Asian countries might
be gloomy.
</P>
<P>
To revitalize the capital market, the government would revoke
the regulation on the limitation of foreign investors in buying
bonds traded in the bourse, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
