<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Studies Satellite Web to Relay Military Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National
Reconnaissance Office (NRO) is studying the feasibility of a
constellation of communication satellite to relay data to and from
military, intelligence and civil spacecraft, U.S. space and
defense officials said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed National Space Communication Program would replace
separate satellite relay systems operated by National Aeronautics
and Space Administration (NASA) and the Department of Defense, the
Defense News weekly quoted the officials as saying in its
September 1-7 edition.
</P>
<P>
The program was planned to start late next decade. The system
also would relay communications to and from NASA's space shuttle,
the international space station and civilian spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
The NRO, which buys and operates U.S. spy satellites, is
developing the relay system requirements with input from the
military and civilian space sectors and U.S. industry officials,
the weekly said. And the system would be owned and operated by the
U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
The defense space architect office, established in 1995, is
planning the mix of satellite systems that will meet the U.S.
military's future needs, it said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government spends about 1 billion dollars annually to
operate its military, intelligence and civilian spacecraft.
</P>
</TEXT>
