<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Participation in ASEM Not Discussed-Alatas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas said today that Asian countries within the Asia-Europe
Meeting (ASEM) have yet to discuss the participation of Myanmar in
the group's summit in London next year.
</P>
<P>
Alatas told reporters before a cabinet meeting that parties
which will participate in the ASEM meeting next April in London
are Asia and West Europe, instead of ASEAN and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Alatas also said that countries attending the summit would meet
individually rather than inter-groups.
</P>
<P>
He said the Asian countries of ASEM are still working on the
requests of India, Pakistan, Australia and New Zealand to attend
the meeting. "We have yet to reach a consensus."
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook recently said Europe would
oppose the participation of any Myanmar representative to the
ASEM, citing the human rights reason.
</P>
<P>
The first ASEM was held in Bangkok last year, attended by the
ASEAN countries, China, South Korea, Japan and 15 European
countries.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) now groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
