<HEADLINE> British PM Urges Scotland to Postpone World Cup Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair urged here today the Scotland Football Association (SFA) to
postpone Saturday's World Cup qualifying match between Scotland
and Belarus as a respect to Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
The funeral of Diana, who was killed in a tragic car crash
Sunday morning, will be held at London's Westminster Abbey
Saturday morning. Most of Britain's sporting organizations have
decided to call off various events on that day.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Britain's Scottish Secretary Donald Dewar
had voiced deep concern over the SFA's decision to go ahead with
the scheduled game.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said this afternoon: "The Prime
Minister has spoken to Donald Dewar and totally supports the
action he is taking to try to persuade the Scottish Football
Association that it would be inappropriate for the game to go
ahead."
</P>
<P>
The Scottish football authorities had decided that the football
match would go ahead in Aberdeen with all the players wearing
black armbands and observing one minute's silence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most players of the Sottish team have attacked the
go-ahead decision with Ally McCoist, the star player, pulling out
of the squad.
</P>
<P>
"Given the circumstances I would not do either myself or the
fans justice on Saturday and I have asked not to be selected,"
McCoist said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
