<HEADLINE> Three E. African Countries Urged to Harmonize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official from the
East African Co-operation (EAC) today called on EAC member states
to harmonize their respective laws to pave the way for the East
African (EA) common market to be set up in 2000.
</P>
<P>
EAC Executive Secretary Francis Muthaura was addressing a
preparatory meeting in Kenya's port city of Mombasa for a
conference of attorney generals from Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
to be held on September 5, the Kenya News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
There was need to identify and explore specific areas of
co-operation which would benefit the three member states, he
noted, as some existing laws might hinder the secretariat's
course of action.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura said that areas of co-operation had been identified
during the phase one, and the next step would focus on specific
recommendations and their implementations.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the meeting said that specific recommendations
included the revival of the court of appeal for east Africa, the
implementation of cross border legal practice and the revival of
the publication of the east African law reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
