<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Chechnya Bargain over Oil Transit Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin Wednesday ruled out the possibility of a compromise
in the transportation of Caspian oil via Chechen territory,
describing it as to be "misplaced", the Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian Fuel and Energy Ministry, it offered
0.43 U.S. dollars for transportation of one ton of oil via
Chechen territory, while the Chechen side proposed that it receive
2.20 U.S. dollars per ton, which includes expenses for
management, guards and so on.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said the figures on which the Russian side is
insisting at the talks on oil transit were not "somebody's
caprice." Russia has a broad experience in the transportation of
energy supplies both on Russian territory and abroad and therefore
the tariffs proposed by the Russian side are dictated by the
situation on the market, he added.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin pointed out that if the issue of transportation of
early Caspian oil via Chechnya is not resolved "we will search for
different ways, and they exist."
</P>
<P>
The joint Russian-Chechen commission held its meetings Tuesday
in the village of Dagomys near the Black Sea resort city of Sochi,
which involved Russian Security Council Secretary Ivan Rybkin and
Chechen First Deputy Prime Minister Movladi Udugov. The talks were
also attended by president of the Chechen oil company Yunko
Khodzhakhmed Yarikhanov.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted Yarikhanov as saying, Chechen President Aslan
Maskhadov has rejected the Russian proposal made by Rybkin on the
transit of Caspian oil across Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov does not agree with the technique of determining the
amount to be paid, Yarikhanov was cited.
</P>
<P>
"Russia must rebuild the (Chechen) oil industry anyway while
Chechnya wants to cash in on the transit of oil," the Chechen oil
company president said. "By insisting on the tariff of 0.43 U.S.
dollars per ton of oil, the Russian Fuel and Energy Ministry is
trying to downgrade Chechnya to a Russian region," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Yuri Lisin, vice president of the Russian
oil pumping company Transneft, arrived in Grozny Wednesday
afternoon to continue the discussion of oil transit with Yarikhanov
later the day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
