<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFBWW Congress Opens in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A three-day 20th congress of
the International Federation of Building and Wood Workers (IFBWW)
started here today with a call for trade unions to review their
effectiveness and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 delegates from 110 countries are attending the
congress which seeks to analyse the role of trade union movements
in the 21th century.
</P>
<P>
The congress will focus on the need for trade unions to adopt
and strengthen their position to best meet workers' needs in
modern societies which were increasingly influenced by the
changing political and economic environments.
</P>
<P>
The IFBWW groups trade unions in the building, wood, forestry
and allied sectors. It currently has 13 million members in 264
trade unions in 110 countries.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, Zimbabwe's public service, labour and
social welfare minister Florence Chitauro said although trade
unions had changed from being "mere agitators" to competent
negotiators in labour disputes, they were still faced with more
challenges.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge of today is for trade unions to be professional
in approach, guided by research and strategic planning ethics by
virtue of the fact that their purview has broadened to include
employment retention and creation," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe government was committed to the idea of
tripartism which promoted dialogue on economic issues between
trade unions, employers and itself, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The government has gone beyond provisions of ILO conventions
in consulting social parters by extending tripartite
consultations on economic decisions," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
