<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Refugees Continue Hunger Strike in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian refugees today
continued their hunger strike for the third straight day in front
of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA) building in the
Lebanese capital of Beirut, protesting its budget cut.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the protesters said UNRWA's budget cut
indicated an end to the agency's services to the Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
"Previous sit-ins did not lead to any results, so we decided
to go on a hunger strike, holding the donor countries responsible
for any human catastrophes," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
UNRWA, founded in 1950, is the sole provider of health and
educational services to 3.3 million Palestinian refugees in the
world, including 360,000 in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The agency's announcement of its budget cut of 7 million
dollars this year on August 20 triggered sit-ins and protests by
Palestinian refugees in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The reduction is reportedly as a result of a 20 million dollar
deficit and lack of contributions from donor nations.
</P>
<P>
The major donor countries for UNRWA are the United States,
Japan, Canada and Sweden. Burden on the host countries, such as
Lebanon, Syria, Egypt and Jordan, has been increasing since the
contributions to the agency have been reducing, local media
reported.
</P>
<P>
The protesters, who are abstaining from food but not water or
cigarettes, said their strike was part of a series of measures
against the agency.
</P>
<P>
"We shall fast day and night until UNRWA's austerity measures
in Lebanon are terminated," said a striker who refused to
disclose his name.
</P>
<P>
He said Palestinian refugees in Jordan, Syria and Gaza Strip
are also on a strike to protest the decision.
</P>
<P>
During the strike, the Lebanese government, which is also
against the budget cuts, sent policemen to the strike site to
help keep order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
