<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Push Cyprus Political Settlement Forward: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The goal of the United States
is to help continue the U.N.-led talks for a Cyprus settlement, a
U.S. ambassador said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with President Glafcos
Clerides, U.S. Ambassador to Cyprus, Kenneth Brill, said that
the U.S. goal is "to keep people focused on how to move
forward a political settlement and to avoid things that cause
tension".
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he believed intercommunal talks would take place
in March, Brill said the goal of the U.S. and of other interested
parties is to see the talks resume once the presidential
elections are over in February next year, and hope that "things
can be done in between to prepare for those, to make them
constructive".
</P>
<P>
The two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct talks held in the
U.S. and Switzerland in July and August, between president
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, ended in
failure because of Denktash's refusal to negotiate a settlement
if the European Union does not postpone accession talks with
Cyprus early next year.
</P>
<P>
Brill announced that Thomas Miller, U.S. State Department
Coordinator for Cyprus will visit the island later this month.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Presidential Emissary for Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke is
also expected to visit Cyprus "some time in the fall", but
his schedule has not been set yet, the U.S. diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that after failure of the two rounds
of U.N.-led intercommunal talks in the last two months, the
U.S. will intensify its peace efforts, trying to bring the two
sides on the island into a negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops and
took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved despite the U.N.
and international community's peace efforts for past 23 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
