<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Scale Illegal Trading in CFCS Exposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A new report published today by
the Environmental Investigation Agency (EIA) exposed a large scale
Europe-wide illegal trade in CFCs, ozone depleting chemicals used
in refrigeration.
</P>
<P>
Production of CFCs has been banned in Europe since January 1,
1995. No import licenses have been granted since January 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, CFCs are traded around Europe and on to a lucrative
market in the United States.
</P>
<P>
EIA estimates the size of the European illegal trade in CFCs at
between 6,000 and 10,000 tons per year. The European Chemical
Industry council has put the figure much higher at 20,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The report entitled "Chilling Facts About a Burning Issue: CFC
Smuggling in the European Union", is the most comprehensive
dossier of information on the illegal CFCs trade in Europe ever
made public.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in London today, EIA Chairman Allan Thornton said:
"This evidence proves that there are large amounts of CFCs in
circulation around Europe, and that the Ozone protection regime is
in danger of unraveling."
</P>
<P>
"European governments must now implement a ban on the sale of
CFCs across the EU and close the loopholes which allow illicit
trade in CFCs to persist," he added.
</P>
<P>
Incidence of skin cancer has reached record levels as ozone
depletion allows more ultraviolet radiation to reach the Earth's
surface.
</P>
<P>
There are now 2,000 reported deaths from skin cancer each year
in Britain alone. It has been estimated that in the U.S. one in 70
Caucasians will contract skin cancer in a "quiet 20th century
epidemic", according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
