<HEADLINE> UNDP Allocates $2 Million for Emergency Response, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Development Program (UNDP)is providing 2 million U.S. dollars to
help the Democratic People's Republic of Korea(DPRK) prepare for
disasters and carry out rehabilitation work following the severe
drought and flooding that have plagued the country in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The assistance will help strengthen the government's ability to
manage international aid, train technicians and emergency workers
and build local capacities in such areas as disaster prevention
and mitigation, environmental protection and agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
Christian Lemaire, UNDP Resident Representative in DPRK, said
that tens of thousands of children are in danger of starving, and
that the situation is particularly precarious for orphans in
nurseries and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
He added that food-aid is not a long-term solution, and that
improving agricultural productivity is a priority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
