<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Press Groups Disgusted by Legal Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Many French photographer and
press institutions today reacted with disgust to the decision by
the French judicial authorities to continue inquiry against six
photographers and one press motorcyclist for pursuing the late
Princess of Wales last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Paris Investigation Court Tuesday decided to inquire into
the responsibility of the photographers in the car crash of Diana,
and could put them on trial for "non assistance to persons in
danger and involuntary homicide and involuntary injury."
</P>
<P>
In a statement published today, the National Federation of
Photo Press Agencies of France (FNAPPI) said: "The condemnation a
priori of the reporter-photographer journalists is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
It also accused some press journalists for "bringing to their
reporter-photographer colleagues heavy and grave accusations"
after the accident took place.
</P>
<P>
The directors of some photo press agencies, considered to be
the best in the world, today also reminded the public that
professional photo journalists have paid a high price for covering
wars and other high risk events around the world.
</P>
<P>
One of the six photographers under investigation, Jacques
Langevin of the Sygma agency, is an award-winning reporter who
covered numerous high risk world events.
</P>
<P>
In an article published in the daily Liberation, Langevin said
that he did not participate in the chase of Diana that night, and
arrived at the scene of the crash in Alma tunnel all by accident.
</P>
<P>
All the press agencies stressed that the only concrete evidence
of the crash is that Henri Paul, the chauffeur of Diana and her
friend Egyptian billionaire Dodi Al Fayed, was drunk and was
speeding the powerful Mercedes at 180 kilometers per hour (110
miles per hour).
</P>
<P>
In a statement published today, the Reporters sans Frontieres
expressed its concern over the "graveness of the charges
maintained" against the six photographers and one motorcyclist.
</P>
<P>
"Reporters sans Frontieres tries to recall that the justice
should be exercised in calmness and sereneness, far from the
pressure of public opinion," it said.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial entitled "Red Carpet for Censorship," the
daily France Soir accused the judicial authorities of imposing
censorship on the photographers by putting them under inquiry
according to the will of the higher authorities.
</P>
<P>
"It is a red carpet, color of the circumstance, that the
justice worked yesterday in honor of the censorship on the
move," said the chief editor of France Soir in the editorial.
</P>
<P>
Roger Therond, the boss of the Paris Match photo magazine, said
that "all people are responsible" and that the "machine is
getting out of control."
</P>
<P>
"There is a phenomenon from the public who, weary of a society
they feel absurd, takes refuge in dreams," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
