<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Calls for Peaceful Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said today that it
takes seriously the threats made by Turkey and the Turkish
Cypriots, but at the same time it continues to pursue peaceful
solutions to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government is preparing for any event, Manolis
Christofides, Cyprus government spokesman, said at a daily press
briefing, but "to their (Turkey's and Turkish Cypriot) bellicose
threats, we reply with propositions for a peaceful solution to the
Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
A settlement of the Cyprus issue "can be achieved only through
peaceful means," he was commenting on the threats made by Serdar
Denktash, the so-called "Vice President" of the Turkish Cypriot
regime in northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Serdar Denktash said recently if the Russian-made missiles were
deployed in Cyprus, the Turkish Cypriots would settle in the
eastern town of Famagusta (Varosha).
</P>
<P>
Famagusta has been a ghost town, from which all residents were
evacuated, since the Turkish military intervention in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council resolution 550 considers
"attempts to settle in any part of Varosha by people other than its
inhabitants as inadmissible and calls for the transfer of this
area to the administration of the U.N."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government signed an agreement with Russia in
January to buy its anti-aircraft missiles. This deal has enraged
Turkey and Turkish Cypriots which have threatened to launch
military strikes against Cyprus if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Delivery of the missiles is expected to be done by autumn next
year. But the Cyprus government said the deal could be canceled if
Turkish Cypriots agreed to Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides'
proposal for demilitarization of the island, or if there was
substantial progress on the Cyprus problem to justify their
non-delivery.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when the Turkey sent
troops took over the northern third of the island in the wake of a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. The
Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Preparing for Re-negotiations with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean military
government of Major Johnny Paul Koroma is 100 days in office
today but officials said there are no plans for any celebrations.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to see how we can offset the blockade and
sanctions imposed by west African leaders last weekend at their
summit (Economic Community of West African States) in Abuja,
Nigeria and provide improved living standards for our people," a
state house official told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Other phone calls to leading government officials received
similar responses.
</P>
<P>
"We are too busy for interviews. We are looking at
alternatives and strategies," was all they could say.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the government is preoccupied with the
task of finding ways to restart negotiations with the ECOWAS'
Committee of Four on Sierra Leone on returning the country to
constitutional rule after the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
So far the government has not issued any official statement to
the blockade and sanction. But according to officials from the
Ministry of Trade, there are enough petroleum products and rice,
which is the country's staple food for the time being.
</P>
<P>
One businessman said, the sectors that could be affected
immediately are likely to be flour, onions and sugar. The price
for a loaf of bread has increased by four times from Monday to
Tuesday with its size shrinking to two-third of its original.
</P>
<P>
The pro-democracy clandestine radio which had openly called
for military intervention said Tuesday that the blockade and
sanction made against the regime "is a direct response of the
disgust of the international community."
</P>
<P>
According to the radio, all officials of the junta and their
relatives are now barred from entering western countries
including Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The government is hard-pressed for talks and two organizations
which are working independently announced Monday they are
"working behind the scenes to get talks started."
</P>
<P>
The groups, the Independent National Mediation Commission led
by one-time Youth Minister Musa Kabia and Mediators for Peace in
Sierra Leone led by businessman Ibrahim Sesay, said they have a
large number of paramount chiefs, university lecturers and
religious leaders supporting them.
</P>
<P>
"We want to urgently get Koroma and Kabbah (the ousted
president) together so that they can solve the current impasse
once and for all. This is our goal," Kabia added.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Ahara Bangali, secretary of state
finance, has been invited to the meeting of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in Hong Kong on September 23.
</P>
<P>
The IMF secretariat stated in a letter that the meeting will
review the activities of the World Bank and IMF and address the
issue of governance and human rights.
</P>
<P>
Bangali told Xinhua that "The World Bank and the IMF cannot
suspend a member country because of its political impasse," a
reference to the non-recognition of the junta government by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
"Sierra Leone is still a member of IMF contrary to rumours
that it has been suspended by the organization," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
