<HEADLINE> AL Chief Voices Concern over Turkish-Israeli War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid today voiced his concern over the
Israeli-Turkish-U.S. war games and their impact on Arab national
security.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his disappointment over the timing of the
Israeli-Turkish-U.S. navy exercises that are scheduled to be held
on November 15-25 in the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
"The military exercises come while the Mideast peace process
came to a standstill," the AL chief told reporters after a meeting
with Turkish Ambassador to Egypt Yasar Yakis.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been stalled since
March when Israel started to build a controversial settlement in
traditional Arab East Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want as
their future capital.
</P>
<P>
He said that "Turkey should have taken into consideration the
strong ties binding Ankara and the Arab world."
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid and the Turkish ambassador discussed the latest
developments of the Arab-Turkish ties and the dimensions of the
Turkish-Israeli military maneuvers during the meeting, which took
place at the request of Yakis.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish ambassador, on his part, reiterated that the
military exercises come within the context of "search and rescue
operations" and are "open to all countries of the region."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Turkish-U.S. joint maneuvers have set off criticism
from Arab countries already concerned about the growing
Israeli-Turkish alliance.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Tuesday that Turkey
and Israel sent a "negative message" to the region by planning to
hold military exercises in the Mediterranean. Syria has also
condemned such war games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
