<HEADLINE> France Urges Turkey to Adopt Open Attitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- France today called on Turkey to
adopt a more open attitude toward ending the division of Cyprus,
but claimed that the future acceptance of Turkey by the European
Union is not directly linked with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"Enlargement of the European Union to Cyprus calls for a
political solution (to the division of the island nation)," said
French Minister of European Affairs, Pierre Moscovici, after
holding a meeting with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission decided in July to start negotiations
next year with Nicosia on the admission of the Greek part of the
Mediterranean island into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
"We told our Turkish friends that they are not the only one in
the problem, but that we hope that there will also be from the
Turkish side a more open attitude toward the future," said
Moscovici.
</P>
<P>
He said that France remains favorable to the wish by Turkey to
join the European Union and hopes that Turkey can soon participate
in the ministerial conference of European Union in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"The European conference is not a pack of consolidation. It is
an ambitious enterprise which should signify that all countries
should be treated as equal on the same departing line," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Turkey first applied for EU membership in 1987, which was
rejected by Brussels in 1989 mainly because of opposition from
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into the northern Turkish part and the
southern Greek part after an invasion by Turkish troops in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The international community recognizes the Greek Cypriot
government as the only legitimate government of Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
