<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Labor Department Releasing Welfare-to-Work Grants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- About 1.1 billion dollars
is on its way to states to help welfare recipients get job
training and experience, said Vice President Al Gore of the United
States Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"These funds represent a dramatic commitment to help break the
cycle of poverty in every state," Gore said at the White House,
where a coalition was discussing how to help welfare recipients
keep jobs once they find them.
</P>
<P>
The new budget law President Bill Clinton signed last month
included three billion dollars for welfare-to-work grants,
including 1.5 billion for the coming year and 1.5 billion for
1999.
</P>
<P>
Cities will compete for 25 percent of the money, sending
applications to the Labor Department administering the program.
But the rest is being awarded based on the number of welfare
recipients who live in each state.
</P>
<P>
In order to prepare mostly long-term welfare recipients to
someday take regular jobs, the grants may be used to subsidize
wages for private or public jobs, provide on-the-job training,
offer community service experience or pay for job readiness and
job placement.
</P>
<P>
The program will target welfare recipients who are in danger of
losing welfare due to time limits, have little education, drug
problems and a poor work history.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile states must spend one dollor of their money for every
two in federal funds they receive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: G-77 Spearheads South-South Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
( by Xu Jianmei )
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Group-77 is dynamically
spearheading South-South cooperation in the fields of banking,
insurance, information exchanges, joint ventures and so on.
</P>
<P>
A draft feasibility study on the proposed G-77 Trade and
Development Bank has been submitted by Kenya, the expected venue
for the bank, to the G-77 Chamber of Commerce and Industry (CCI)
steering committee, CCI Chairman Tariq Sayeed said here today.
</P>
<P>
G-77's 132 member states will invest altogether one billion
U.S. Dollars as the initial capital of the bank which is aimed at
stirring export-oriented growth among development countries, said
Sayeed.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has provided more than 100,000 Dollars
to finance the operation of the Experts Committee of the planned
bank, whose official feasibility study is expected to be
completed by November this year.
</P>
<P>
G-77 is also preparing a Joint Ventures Conference in China
and a trade exhibition in India, both set for next year, in a bid
to boost economic information exchanges and cooperation within
the third world, said Sayeed.
</P>
<P>
A just-ended meeting of G-77 CCI steering committee
decided to set up a 15-member board in charge of the G-77
Joint Ventures centre. Each continent can hold five seats at the
board, he said.
</P>
<P>
China, "a leading role in South-South cooperation", will be
one of the five representatives on behalf of Asia in the board,
Sayeed told Xinhua, speaking highly of the fruitful development
of joint ventures in China.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that CCI has been installing a trade information
network to provide timely charged information to all the
developing nations.
</P>
<P>
"A G-77 web will be set up on the Internet where G-77 members
can post information on marketing products. Finally a data base of
information will be created for use by all CCI members," he said.
</P>
<P>
The G-77, the major forum for South-South cooperation, has
also made certain progress in setting up a re-insurance company
and a permanent exhibition authority, Sayeed said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he announced that the venue of the next CCI General
Assembly will be chosen among Kenya, Nigeria, Morocco and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
At the opening of the CCI meeting Monday, Sayeed called on
G-77 members to adopt a new strategy to boost South-South
cooperation and finally evolve a balanced, just and equitable
global economic order.
</P>
<P>
"The current global behavior indeed calls for evolving a new
strategy," he noted, citing a recorded 2,100-billion-U.S.-Dollar
foreign debt of the third world in 1996 and trade barriers by
developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Facing the situation, the developing countries first "should
unite ourselves and forge cooperation to address the crucial
issues emanating from trade barriers, conditionalities of IMF,
problems of trade deficit and mounting trade burden," he said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the G-77 members " should try to improve our system
by adopting modern techniques both for production and investment"
and "make collective efforts" to remove invisible trade barriers
like anti-dumping, environment and child labor, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
This is "a two-pronged strategy" the developing world has to
do, he announced.
</P>
<P>
The developing countries now account for about 25 percent of
the world trade, compared with 20 percent a decade ago, noted
Sayeed.
</P>
<P>
The Karachi-based G-77 group, which comprises of 132
developing countries from Asia, Africa, Latin America and the
Pacific and Carribean region, was founded at the first U.N.
Conference on Trade and Development meeting in Geneva in 1964.
</P>
<P>
The group set up CCI in 1986 in a bid to mobilize the
participation of the private sector for economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
