<HEADLINE> Sudan, Uganda to improve ties: Sudanese President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Bashir said here today that the coming days would witness positive
developments in relations between Sudan and Uganda and the peace
process in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return today from a tour to South Africa, Tanzania
and Zambia, Bashir said in a statement at the airport that his
trip was successful.
</P>
<P>
He said he held talks with Ugandan President Yuri Musevini
during his visit to South Africa and discussed ways of resolving
differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Their talks were sponsored by South African President Nelson
Mandela and in the presence of Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
in his capacity as chairman of the current Organization of African
Unity session.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the failure of the southern Sudanese rebel leader
John Garang to attend the talks, Bashir said "this was not the
first time that Garang avoided meeting with a Sudanese government
delegation."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his readiness "to meet with Garang at any time or
place."
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had signed the Khartoum peace agreement
in April with six southern Sudanese rebel movements. But the
Garang faction, the largest rebel movement, boycotted the peace
move.
</P>
<P>
Mandela tried to arrange a meeting between the two Sudanese
leaders during Bashir's visit to the southern African countries,
but Garang turned down the proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
