<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Repeats Russian Opposition against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia still "categorically
objects" to the Baltic countries' plans to join the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said today.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Lithuania's capital Vilnius to take part in
the 11-nation summit on security and cooperation in Europe
scheduled on September 5-6, Chernomyrdin said if Lithuania,
Latvia and Estonia join the NATO "there will inevitably arise
extra sources of mistrust and suspicion" in their relations with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia feels alarmed by the fact that the states of the
Baltic region are mentioned in the Madrid (NATO summit)
declaration, even though they are mentioned in connection with
future stages of expansion of the alliance and not as (states that
will) joint it immediately.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin noted "We believe that joining any bloc to ensure
the security of a state is not only a hopelessly obsolete
principle but also one that can lead to new dividing lines."
</P>
<P>
The premier said Russia is ready to do everything to build
relations of good-neighborly attitudes and cooperation in the
Baltic region.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that Russia regard the strengthening of the
security of the Baltic countries as an important element of work on
a model for general and comprehensive security under a decision by
the OSCE (Organization for Security and cooperation in Europe).
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, meanwhile, expressed skepticism about the
promised reform of NATO, saying that "it is still not quite clear
what strategy the alliance has for the transformation of its
military or political structures." 
</P>
</TEXT>
