<HEADLINE> French President to Visit Mauritania This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
will pay a two-day state visit to Mauritania to show his
"attachment to the African continent," said French presidential
spokeswoman Catherine Colonna today.
</P>
<P>
"Testimony to the line of particular solidarity which exists
between France and Africa, this trip will also be turned toward
the future," she said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, which is his fifth to Africa since becoming
president in May 1995, Chirac will announce a number of programs
to be offered by France to help Mauritania develop its water
processing capability, its agriculture and in its fight against
drought, said Colonna.
</P>
<P>
In the Mauritanian capital Nouakchott, Chirac will make a
speech on Friday laying out the new policy of France when
cooperating with African countries, which will be focused on the
needs of the African people and highlights the partnership between
France and Africa, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will also visit the desert region of Atar in the
northwestern African nation on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine and former Prime
Minister Pierre Messmer, who was governor of Atar during the
French colonial rule in Mauritania, will accompany Chirac in the
visit.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said last week that France would adapt its Africa policy
to the great changes going on in the African continent, while
reinforcing its traditional relations with African nations.
</P>
<P>
He said that France would reevaluate its defense agreements
with a number of African countries and reaffirmed France's policy
of no interference in the internal conflicts of some African
countries, such as the Congo Republic and the Central African
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
