<HEADLINE> Turkey Defends Joint Maneuvers with U.S., Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said today its planned
joint naval exercises with the United States and Israel are not
directed against any other country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry
deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that the war games will be
"a search and rescue operation" devoid of any strategic importance.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said that the U.S.-Israeli-Turkish joint
exercises are expected to be held in east Mediterranean off the
coast of Israel some time between November 15-25.
</P>
<P>
The announcement in June of the tripartite maneuvers prompted
severe criticism from some Arab nations, which have already been
on alert of the growing Turkish-Israeli military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa had said at a press
conference that the maneuvers "represented a negative message."
</P>
<P>
"We think that the reactions which emerged are probably based
on the fact that the real objectives of the exercise are not well
understood," Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
He added that any Arab state could join in the war games if
they like.
</P>
<P>
The deputy spokesman, however, declined to give the exact date
for the war games, saying November is "a possible time".
</P>
<P>
A Turkish military delegation will visit Israel next month to
make specific arrangements for the exercises, according to
earlier reports.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Israeli military alliance have caused worry and
concern among the Arab states, which accused Turkey, a
predominantly Mulism but officially secular country, of betraying
the interests of the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed two defense and military agreements with Israel
last year to allow, among other things, both countries' air planes
to train in each other's airspace. Turkey has also asked an Israeli
industrial company to upgrade 54 Turkish fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
