<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. General Stresses Need of Land Mines on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A top U.S. general on
Wednesday called the Korean Peninsula a "unique" place that should
be exempted from banning the use of land mines.
</P>
<P>
Gen. John Tilelli, commander in charge of U.S. and South Korean
troops on the peninsula, told a group of reporters that the
peninsula is "unique" because "it is an area... where hostilities
could occur."
</P>
<P>
He stress the Korean peninsula is one of the most heavily
militarized area in the world, and only a truce -- not a peace
treaty -- exists between the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
(DPRK) and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"It is a vestige of the Cold War," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are tens of thousands of land mines used by American and
South Korean troops in the demilitarized zone that divides DPRK
from South Korea where 37,000 U.S. troops are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Tilelli said The United States uses the land mines in the
peninsula out of "humanitarian" consideration.
</P>
<P>
"As the commander on the ground, I think protecting the lives
of the soldiers, sailors, airmen and marines and civilians on the
southern side... is a humanitarian issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The general said he was pleased with the Clinton
administration's stand at an international conference on banning
land mines currently underway in Norway. Washington is seeking an
exemption for mines on the Korean Peninsula and for certain types
of mines.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether there is any technical options to replace land
mines, Tilelli replied: "There is not right now a replacement
for land mines." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
