<HEADLINE> European Shares Slip on New Interest Rate Worries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Main stock markets in Europe
all gave up their early gains to end either lower or little
changed Wednesday, undermined by Wall Street's profit-taking and
new worries about possible German interest rate rise.
</P>
<P>
The London market, Europe's largest, had surged ahead by 1.5
percent or 75.1 points to 5,027.3,000 earlier today, boosted by
the Dow's overnight strong gains, before declining to stand only
0.5 percent, or 24.7 points higher at 4,976.9 by close.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that profit-takers shaved some of the market's
dramatic gains of the last two sessions.
</P>
<P>
The market took little notice of a weaker-than-expected UK
purchasing managers' report on services, although the survey gave
gilts a lift.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt ended 1.4 percent firmer, lifted by
New York's rally Tuesday. It closed off the top but still up 56.28
points at 4,103.65 as stronger-than- expected industrial output
data for July trimmed prices in late trade.
</P>
<P>
Stocks on the Paris bourse fell back after big gains in the
morning, as euphoria faded with the easier dollar.
Dollar-sensitive stocks were the hardest-hit. The CAC-40 index
closed down 3.23 points at 2,917.92. 
</P>
</TEXT>
