<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Committees to Be Formed in Kenya to Speed up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The second meeting of Kenya's
Inter-Parties Parliamentary Group (IPPG) today decided to appoint
three committees to prepare recommendations on various reforms
following two-day dialogue between opposing parties.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 members of parliament attending the meeting mandated
the 13-member Co-ordinating Committee to draft resolutions for
the meeting which started here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A technical committee comprising nine Members of Parliament
from the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) and
opposition parties will make recommendations on constitutional,
legal and administrative reforms.
</P>
<P>
Another technical committee comprising five MPs from the
ruling and opposition parties will develop recommendations on the
draft electoral code and draft regulations to govern the
operations of the Electoral Commission.
</P>
<P>
An IPPG Committee comprising seven MPs will recommend to the
IPPG plenary meeting a collective resolution regarding the
current problems of insecurity and banditry in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Co-ordinating Committee has recommended that the dialogue
between KANU and the Opposition lawmakers be concluded in one
month time to enable Kenya's parliament enact the required
legislation before the impending general elections to be held
later this year.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the meeting unanimously endorsed a
proposal by Cabinet Minister Simeon Nyachae to extend the mandate
of the Co-ordinating Committee.
</P>
<P>
At today's session, Oki Ombaka from opposition Ford-Kenya
proposed that since the reforms dialogue is the seventh
parliament's best initiative, the committee's status should be
formalized through a parliamentary motion.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the MPs unanimously endorsed their unwavering
commitment to reform dialogue and embarked on a smooth debate on
a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
At the first meeting held last Thursday, the KANU and
Opposition MPs unanimously resolved to take up their
parliamentary roles to spearhead reform dialogue instead of the
National Convention Executive Council, an umbrella body of
opposition parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
