<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls for Fraternal Ties with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today called for co-existence and fraternity in the
relations between Turkey and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old president made the remark while meeting with
Ali Tuygan, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel's special envoy
and Deputy Under-Secretary of Foreign Affairs, who delivered a
message of Demirel to the Iranian president.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides did not reveal any content of the message
or the timetable for returning their ambassadors to each other's
capital.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that exchange of views and visits by the two
countries' officials would pave the way for better relations
between them.
</P>
<P>
"We should understand that our enemies and the countries
which are against peace in the region and against strong
relations between Tehran and Ankara want to see disputes
appearing in the region, especially between such leading
countries as Iran and Turkey," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish envoy described his meeting with the Iranian
president as "useful" in solving the diplomatic crisis caused by
expulsion of ambassadors from each side in February.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara-Tehran relations became strained in February as Ankara
protested to Tehran for Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Reza Baqeri's
comments in favor of Islamic law at an Islamists rally in the
Ankara district of Sincan.
</P>
<P>
Ali Tuygan, who arrived here Tuesday night, had a talk with
Mohsen Amin-Zadeh, Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for
Asia-Pacific Affairs, before delivering the message to the
Iranian new president this morning. 
</P>
