<HEADLINE> Pro-Kurdish Press Conference Aborted in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish police today
aborted a press conference to be held by pro-Kurdish activists in
Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
About 270 activists, planning to hold a press conference this
morning, were barred by the police from leaving their hotels, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Kurdish activists, including Europeans and Turks, are
among those who gathered in Turkey under a "Peace Train" plan to
rally support for the Kurdish people in the country.
</P>
<P>
They arrived in Istanbul Tuesday evening from Ankara where they
were reportedly blocked by police from entering the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul police had warned the activists that their planned
press conference would constitute an illegal act, forcing them to
issue a press release instead, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Kurds have been fighting a separatist war against Turkish
government troops since 1984 for the establishment of an
independent state in the southeastern region of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ankara launched repeated attacks against the rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, and even carried out cross-border
military operations in north Iraq in order to wipe out PKK
resistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
