<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Be Cautious in Choosing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) were urged today to be on alert
when assessing demands and suitability of potential investors in the
mining industry in their countries.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the SADC mining sector said in Blantyre, Malawi, that it
is important to make the access in the interest and aspirations of
their citizens because some mining companies and financiers have a
tendency of adopting hard and uncompromising stand on African
countries by adopting predetermined set of prescriptions which are
disproportionately biased, the Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press on the activities of the SADC mining sector in
the region, its coordinator John Chanda charged that investors have
been also playing down the attractive geological potential by
pronouncing physical infrastructure, security and political risk as
major factors affecting investment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"It is in the light of these exploitative tendencies the SADC
committee of mining ministers approved the protocol which serve as a
vehicle for regional integration," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is necessary for SADC to commit itself to a
suitable cooperative mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Chanda said although the performance of SADC's mining industry
compared to the world mineral industry has declined due to lack of
investment in recent years, there is still scope for increasing
exploration, development and exploitation of mineral resources in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The protocol to be considered by the SADC council of ministers
Thursday is based on four principles including harmonization of
national and regional policies, strategies and programs related
to the development and exploitation of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
The protocol to be submitted to the SADC summit to be held next
Monday in Blantyre also includes the provision of information
exchange, enhancement of technological capacity, common standards,
small scale mining, environment protection, occupational health and
safety and the promotion of private sector participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Members Urged to Invest in Tourism Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior Mauritian official
urged the Southern African Development Community (SADC) member
states to invest more in the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Soobaha Fowdur, Principal Assistant Secretary of the Mauritian
Tourism Ministry, made these remarks Tuesday in Blantyre, a
southern city of Malawi while briefing the press on the operation
of the SADC tourism coordinating section under the chairmanship
of Mauritius, according to the Zambia News Agency (ZANA) today.
</P>
<P>
However, Fowdur didn't give any details on the operation of
the coordinating section.
</P>
<P>
He said that the development of tourism in Southern Africa is
hampered by the under-development of hotels, transport and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
SADC members need to invest in these three sectors if they are
to promote the tourism industry, said Fowdur, stressing that
these sectors are some of the attractions in the industry.
</P>
<P>
The ZANA quoted Fowdur as saying that some tourists in Europe,
south and north America like traveling in the SADC region but are
reluctant to come because of the "poor infrastructure" in
tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Mauritian official also urged SADC members to expedite the
proposed introduction of "univisas" to attract more tourists in
the region, which is losing foreign exchange by insisting on
tourists to have visas before they could be allowed entry in the
SADC countries.
</P>
<P>
The SADC, which was founded in 1992 and aimed at promoting
economic integration toward a fully developed common market in
the Southern Africa, pays much attention to tourism and considers
it to be a major element of the regional integration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
