<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-03 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Major Tourist Assets Under Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's state-owned Holding
Company for Housing, Tourism and Cinema (HCHTC) announced today it
plans to sell all of its assets within a three-year privatization
process.
</P>
<P>
The company was established in 1991 with the primary objective
of organizing the sale of its portfolio of state-owned companies
(affiliated companies) to private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Currently, it has 76 assets and 16 companies, with businesses
ranging from tourism to housing, construction and industry.
</P>
<P>
In six months starting from December 1 with the opening of the
bidding process, 24 companies are scheduled for sale, Moustafa
Eid, chairman of the company, told a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Eid expressed hope that by the end of 1999, all the assets of
this public company will be turned into private ownership.
</P>
<P>
The total value of the assets on sale is estimated at 5 to 6
billion Egyptian pounds (1.47-1.77 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to reports, the five-star Cairo Hilton will be sold
for 500 million pounds (147.06 million dollars), and Mariot is
valued at 1 billion pounds (294.12 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The actual sales of these assets to the international investors
will be launched at the Euromoney Conference to be held here on
September 9 and 10, said the company chairman.
</P>
<P>
The operational hotels offered for sale include several elite
names in the catering service such as Aswan Oberoi Hotel, Helnan
Shepherd Hotel and Isis Floating Hotel, said the business
sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
