<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Analysts See 32-billion-Dollar Surplus in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The strong U.S. economy and
the budget deal between President Bill Clinton and the Congress
should produce a budget surplus of 32 billion dollars in 2002 that
would grow even larger, The New York Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a report by the U.S. Congressional Budget Office, the
paper said that without the bipartisan budget agreement, U.S.
budget deficits would continue unabated for at least a decade.
</P>
<P>
In their annual summertime fiscal update, nonpartisan budget
analysts in the U.S. Congress said the budget package Clinton
signed on August 5 would, as promised, help deliver surpluses in
2002 and the years immediately following. After hitting 32 billion
dollars in 2002, surpluses are expected to shrink a bit, then grow
to 86 billion dollars by 2007, the last year the budget office
examined.
</P>
<P>
But the analysts also warned that a weakened economy or failure
to live under the budget deal's spending strictures would
jeopardize those unusually healthy numbers.
</P>
<P>
A recession could add 100 billion dollars a year in unforeseen
red ink, they said.
</P>
<P>
They also said that even with the surpluses, a major problem
awaited on the horizon: the beginning of the retirement of the
huge baby boom generation late next decade, driving up costs for
many federal programs.
</P>
<P>
"Legislators will need to take substantial further action to
set the growth in Social Security and Medicare spending at
sustainable levels and to prevent spiraling deficits in the next
century," the budget office said.
</P>
<P>
The Congressional budget office had said that it expects this
year's deficit to be 34 billion dollars, down from last year's 107
billion.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government deficit has declined steadily since 1992
when it hit a record-high 290 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
