<HEADLINE> US Mediator Holds Talks With Israeli Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. mediator Dennis Ross
held lengthy talks today with an Israeli delegation ahead of
Madeleine Albright's first trip since she became the secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
Ross and State Department officials avoided any description of
Ross's four-hour meeting with Israeli Cabinet secretary Danny
Naveh and Uzi Arad, foreign policy advisor to Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to take the Middle East trip next Tuesday
and will meet leaders of Israel, the Palestinian Authority, Egypt,
Jordan, Syria, Saudi Arabia and possibly Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley, replying reporters'
questions, declined to list the issues Ross and then Albright
would discuss with the Palestinians and Israelis. However, he
noted the security situation had improved since a twin suicide
bomb killed 17 people at a Jerusalem market on July 30.
</P>
<P>
Foley also called on Israel to release all taxes withheld from
Palestinian workers. And he criticized Jewish settlers who hurled
stones at Palestinian workers on a U.S.-funded road project in
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
After his meeting with Ross, Israeli Cabinet secretary Naveh
said the Palestinians had to "fight terrorist organizations and
infrastructure" before the peace process could advance.
</P>
<P>
"We believe it is crucial they will take these measures and
they will take these steps in terms of fighting terrorism if we
want to see further progress in the peace process," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Ross will meet with a Palestinian delegation headed by top
negotiators Mahmoud Abbas and Saeb Erekat late this week.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have said they will not resume talks with
Israel unless it stops work on a Jewish housing project in
traditionally Arab East Jerusalem that began in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
