<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Leading Economic Index Goes Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index of
Leading Indicators, the gauge indicating the trend of the U.S.
economy, rose 0.3 percent in July to 104.1, according to its
designer, the New York-based Conference Board.
</P>
<P>
The calculations show that six of the 10 leading economic
indicators rose in July. The most significant increases are
average weekly initial claims for state unemployment insurance and
stock prices.
</P>
<P>
The leading index increased 0.1 percent in June, an upward
revision of 0.1 percent, and increased 0.2 percent in May, a
downward revision of 0.1 percent. During the six-month period
through July, the index increased 1.1 percent and eight of the 10
leading economic indicators advanced.
</P>
<P>
The composite indexes are the key elements in an analytic
system designed to signal peaks and troughs in the business cycle,
according to the research group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
