<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Promises Compromise in Talks on N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Gerry Adams, the leader of
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republic Army (IRA),
promised here today that his party would go into talks on the
future of Northern Ireland in a spirit of compromise.
</P>
<P>
Adams, who is on a lobbying and fund-raising tour of the United
States, told a press conference that his party would go into the
talks "in a spirit of generosity, accommodation and preparedness
to come to a compromise."
</P>
<P>
Adams arrived here Tuesday and is expected to meet with U.S.
political leaders, including National Security Adviser Sandy
Berger at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The British government, satisfied that the IRA is committed to
a cease-fire announced in July, invited Sinn Fein for the first
time ever to all-party talks later this month in Belfast on a
settlement to years of conflict in the British province.
</P>
<P>
However, arguing that the IRA must give up their weapons, some
pro-British parties in the province, including the dominant Ulster
Unionist Party, have not yet agreed to take part in the talks.
</P>
<P>
"The Ulster Unionist Party (UUP) is willing to participate in
talks with Sinn Fein/IRA if they show that they are an
ex-terrorist group by decommissioning their weapons," said a UUP
statement issued in Washington on Adams' visit.
</P>
<P>
"We see no purpose in negotiating with an active terrorist
group," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Adams said he hoped and expected that the Unionists would take
part in the talks when they open.
</P>
<P>
"We will say to them: `The door is open, your seat is here,
come and join us, come and do it on the 15th of September, do it
as quickly as possible,'" he said.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that UUP leader David Trimble take part in the
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
