<HEADLINE> Diana's Funeral Procession Route Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The Buckingham Palace announced
here this afternoon that the funeral procession route of Princess
Diana would be extended and begin from Diana's London home
Kensington Palace.
</P>
<P>
The original procession route, which was from St James's Palace
to the Westminster Abbey, had been criticized as being too short.
</P>
<P>
A Buckingham Palace spokesman said that the procession plan was
changed because of safety considerations.
</P>
<P>
"We've always tried to consider a way of lengthening the route
in such a way that more people would be able to see the procession
in safety," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said that it was right that
the route was lengthened and as many people as possible involved
so they could express their sense of respect to Diana, who was
killed in a Paris car crash early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The Downing Street also indicated this evening that the
presence of politicians at the funeral will be kept to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Blair, Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott and
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook would attend the funeral, Downing
Street sources said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of Britain's main opposition parties and all the
surviving former prime ministers have also been invited to
participate. 
</P>
