<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Leaders (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li said that the Chinese side believes that past experience, if
not forgotten, can be a guide for the future, and in this way
China will look to the future and maintain friendship with Japan
for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
"We have taken note of the fact that the Japanese leaders have
made it clear several times recently that they will face up to
history, acknowledge aggression, be introspective, and sincerely
apologize," Li noted, saying that that would be conducive to
maintaining the political basis of bilateral relations and helping
enhance understanding and trust between Japan and its Asian
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the Japanese government can provide Japanese
youth with a correct historical viewpoint in the spirit of being
responsible for history," he said
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said that the cabinet of former Japanese Prime
Minister Murayama Tomiichi said officially, concerning the
historical issue, on August 15, 1995, that Japan recognizes that,
because of its invasion and colonial rule, it brought great losses
and suffering to many Asian nations, and it sincerely apologizes.
</P>
<P>
This is the official stance of the Japanese government,
Hashimoto said, and as a cabinet member at that time, he
participated in the decision, and that he has stuck to it so far.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that he will visit the northeastern part of
China as Japanese Prime Minister for the first time to demonstrate
that he is interested in looking to the future on the basis of
correctly understanding history.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that Japan will continue to take the path of
peaceful development, which is the desire of the Japanese people,
and that Japan will never take the militaristic road or become a
military power.
</P>
