<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Proposes Lower Taxes in Sweden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 7 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has called for Sweden to cut taxes and public
expenditure to reduce unemployment and boost its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The IMF board said in a report assessing Sweden's economic
policy that such measures would create more jobs in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
It said the Swedish strategy to halve visible unemployment by
expanding the educational system could hardly work -- partly
because of increased public expenditure incurred by the
educational reform.
</P>
<P>
While hailing Sweden's target of building a budget surplus
equal to two percent of gross domestic product, the IMF board
disagreed with Sweden's plan to offer elderly people early
retirement.
</P>
<P>
The board praised Sweden for the efficient ordering of its
public finances, solving its banking crisis in the early 1990's
and successfully controlling inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
