<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Leaders (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li said that the Taiwan issue is China's internal affair that
no country has the right to interfere in and that the Chinese
government's stand on this is clear and consistent.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government and the Chinese people will not accept
any action aiming at directly or indirectly including Taiwan in
Japan-US security co-operation," Li added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Japanese government should be clear on this,
and emphasized, "We hope the Japanese side attaches the utmost
attention to China's position and respects it."
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said that the Japanese government fully understood
the Chinese government's stance on the Taiwan issue when it
normalized ties with China. Taiwan is an inalienable part of the
People's Republic of China and the government of the People's
Republic is the sole, legal representative of China, he added, and
that Japan only maintains unofficial relations with Taiwan and
does not support "two Chinas" or Taiwan independence.
</P>
<P>
He told Li that Japan regards the Taiwan issue as an issue for
the Chinese people and that the two sides of the Taiwan Straits
should seek a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
Japan will act cautiously on the basis of the Japan-China Joint
Statement and the Japan-China Treaty of Peace and Friendship, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Li spoke highly of the development of Sino-Japanese economic
ties and expressed the hope that the two sides expand co-operation
on the basis of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said they are happy to see that China and Japan
have reached a consensus in signing a new fishery agreement.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said it is good that negotiations between Japan and
China on the WTO issue had a breakthrough recently, and that Japan
will continue to support China's entry into the organization.
</P>
<P>
Li said it is good that the Sino-Japanese negotiations have had
a breakthrough on the issue and that he hopes Japan will continue
to play a positive role and will try to solve the remaining
problems in a constructive way.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to continue talks to reach a bilateral
agreement soon, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also spoke about Japan's proposals on co-operation in
environmental protection and energy, to which Li replied that
China is a country where the environment, energy and agriculture
are some of the most important issues.
</P>
<P>
China has always valued international co-operation and
exchanges in these areas, Li said, and the two countries can
further explore co-operation.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers agreed that a frequent exchange of
visits between the two countries' leaders is important for
increasing mutual understanding and advancing bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto invited Li to visit Japan this year, and for the
invitation Li extended thanks.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, Li and his wife Zhu Lin held a banquet in honor
of Hashimoto, his wife, and their delegation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
