<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Leaders Hold Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng, holding talks
today with visiting Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto,
said that China hopes the visit will yield positive results and
enhance bilateral ties in a healthy and steady way.
</P>
<P>
Li said he hopes the two sides discuss Sino-Japanese relations
and issues of common concern in a frank way and improve the
bilateral relationship that is based on the Sino-Japanese Joint
Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of Peace and Friendship.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 25th anniversary of normalization of
diplomatic ties between the two countries. In reviewing those 25
years, Li said that China believes the bilateral ties are good on
the whole and that the two countries' leaders have maintained
rather close contacts and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and Japan have had much political, trade,
economic and technological co-operation that is important to both
sides.
</P>
<P>
The present-day Sino-Japanese relationship is the result of
efforts of the older-generation of politicians, Li said, and that
this hard-won achievement should be treasured by both sides.
</P>
<P>
He said that for historical reasons there are still problems in
the bilateral relations that shouldn't be neglected.
</P>
<P>
As long as the two sides stick to the principles of the joint
statement and the friendship treaty, and work in a spirit of
mutual respect and seek common ground while reserving differences,
and have frank dialogues and friendly consultations, these
problems can be solved in a proper way, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Both countries should develop good-neighborly friendly
relations of co-operation oriented toward the 21st century, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"To this end," Li went on, "both sides should make an effort,
take a strategic perspective of lasting interest in bilateral
ties, properly deal with the relationship, strictly follow the
joint statement and the friendship treaty, and safeguard the
political foundation for the bilateral ties."
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said his visit is an important step that is oriented
toward the future and that the Japanese government's consistent
stand is one of promoting Japan-China relations in keeping with
the joint statement and friendship treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said that a stable bilateral relationship is important for
both countries and conducive to peace and prosperity in Asia, the
Pacific and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Since the two countries normalized diplomatic ties 25 years
ago, he said, bilateral relations have advanced a great deal, and
the reform and opening up in China has brought many opportunities
for bilateral cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Japanese government will continue to work
for bilateral friendship and support China's reform and opening up
drive.  More
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
