<HEADLINE> Botswana Investigates Sex Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Allegations, published
in Zambia, that Botswana and Zamiba were conduits for children
trafficking for the international sex tourism trade were being
investigated, Botswana's permanent secretary for foreign affairs
Ernest Mpofu said in Gaborone today.
</P>
<P>
An Africa child watch report claimed 16 Zambian teenage girls
had been sent to Botwwana to await arrangements to be sent to Far
East.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Mpofu as
reporting that he had instructed police and immigration officials
to investigate a report from the Botwswanan high commissioner in
Lusaka that a farmer in Kassane, northern Botswana, a tourist
area, was involved.
</P>
<P>
There have been no previous reports in Botswana of such
trafficking, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
A farming source said farmers often encouraged young illegal
immigrants, male and female, to work on their farms and in their
homes.
</P>
<P>
The work was not a favorite of Botswana, even the unemployed.
However, if farmers were caught employing "illegals", they would
be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
The young people were poorly paid, but there had been no
reports of their being physically or sexually abused. 
</P>
</TEXT>
