<HEADLINE> Mozambique, S. Africa, Swaziland to Start Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique, South Africa
and Swaziland will launch a passenger service train to link the
three southern African countries in November this year.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the three neighbouring countries are
introducing such a railway service, Swazi State Radio reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the train will run between Swaziland's capital
city of Mbabane, South Africa's city of Durban and the Mozambican
capital, Maputo.
</P>
<P>
The service among the three countries is being introduced in
the spirit of the Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Communication and tourism are mong priorities of the 12-member
SADC, formed in 1992 to set up a free trade zone and to promote
economic integration in the region. 
