<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Troops to Undergo Training in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- German troops will touch African
soil for the first time since World War II to join a training
program next month with French troops, the French Defense Ministry
said today.
</P>
<P>
The training involving 70 German soldiers will mark the first
German military deployment in Africa since combat between German
Facist troops, known as Afrikakorps, led by Marshal Erwin Rommel,
and the Allied Forces in North Africa from 1941 to 1943.
</P>
<P>
Seventy Bundesher soldiers and 70 French soldiers from the
Franco-German Joint Brigade will be trained in an equatorial
forestry commando center of the French army near Libreville,
capital of Gabon, where 600 French troops are stationed under a
defense treaty.
</P>
<P>
The 5,200-troop Franco-German Joint Brigade, stationed in
southwest Germany, was created 10 years ago and put under the
command of the five-nation European Corps.
</P>
<P>
Germany sent a sanitary unit to the United Nations
multi-national peace-keeping force in Somalia in 1993 and joined
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's Stabilization Force in
the former Yugoslavia in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
