<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Beats Nepal in Regional Football Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan defeated Nepal 2-0
at the opener of the first South Asian Football Federation (SAFF)
Championship here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani team jumped to a 1-0 lead at the 26th minute
through Muhammad Nauman.
</P>
<P>
The National Dashrath Stadium of Nepal, which seats 25,000, had
a full capacity for the match. The audience, braving a 30 degrees
centigrade temperature, were in high spirits and applause and
sound of drums burst now and then.
</P>
<P>
But when the Pakistani team scored another goal to seal the win
24 minutes after the second half, some Nepali spectators began to
throw empty plastic bottles and bags to vent their unhappiness.
</P>
<P>
Ten minutes before the match ended, the Nepali team tried for
goal twice but both were foiled by the goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese have put high hopes on its national team. The All
Nepal Football Association (ANFA) has promised that it will reward
the Nepalese team one million rupees if it wins.
</P>
<P>
The nine-day tournament, joined by Nepal, Pakistan, Bangladesh,
the Maldives, India and Sri Lanka, is played on a
league-and-knockout basis.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will play the Maldives on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The tournament, the biggest ever in the region, is being
organized jointly by the ANFA and the SAFF and is being sponsored
by the Asian Football Confederation.
</P>
<P>
The winner will take home the purse of 50,000 U.S. dollars,
the runner-up will get 25,000 dollars, while the teams coming
third and fourth will take home 15,000 dollars and 10,000 dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The SAFF championship, which will be held every two years, aims
at boosting the football in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, India, Bangladesh, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Pakistan
and the Maldives were all ranked below 110th by the International
Football Federation (FIFA), the world football governing body.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, India, Bangladesh, Nepal, Sri Lanka, Pakistan and
the Maldives ranked 19th, 24th, 27th, 28th, 31st and 34th
respectively in the Asian hierarchy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
