<HEADLINE> Hakkinen Stripped of Third Place in Belgium GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- World motorsports ruling body
FIA stripped Mika Hakkinen here on Thursday of his third place
finish in the Belgium Grand Prix nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
His McLaren team has been fined 50,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
They were found guilty of using a non conforming fuel.
</P>
<P>
However FIA accepted that both McLaren and their fuel suppliers
had acted in good faith and has simply made an unintentional
mistake.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's decision allowed Williams driver Jacques Villeneuve
to move a point closer to world championship leader Michael
Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve, who finish sixth in Belgium, now moves up into
fifth spot and gains an extra championship point.
</P>
<P>
Schumacher has 66 points and Villenueve 55 with five races left.
</P>
<P>
The 'McLaren Affair' began in practice when a petrol sample
from Hakkinen's McLaren was found to be different from that
registered with officials.
</P>
<P>
Hakkinen was initially relegated to the back of the starting
grid and his team fined. However, the sanctions were suspended on
appeal by the team, pending further investigations and Hakkinen
was able to start on the third row of the grid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
