<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Hong Kong Making Last Dash Preparing for WB/IMF  Annual Meetings (2) (By Chang Kefei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The planning division has rented 250 saloon cars and trained
drivers for the service of VIPs, including state leaders, finance
ministers and central bank governors from 181 member countries and
regions, and officials of international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of delegates is likely to reach a climax on
September 19 and 20, when a total of 150 official delegations will
fly in, according to Ng.
</P>
<P>
As to accommodations, he said his planning division had
reserved 7,000 rooms in 44 Hong Kong hotels two years before for
participants in the Meetings.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, we have arranged three-night cultural programs to
show to the world that Hong Kong is a melting point of the Chinese
and Western culture," said Ng.
</P>
<P>
Ng has had his hands full since 1994, when the Board of
Governors of the World Bank and IMF chose Hong Kong as the venue
for the 1997 Meetings, to be held nearly three months after it
became a SAR of China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
China is the host of the 1997 Meetings, while Hong Kong is the
implementing agency to deliver the service. Ng said his planning
division has coordinated with a preparatory team led by the
Chinese Ministry of Finance and joined by other agencies under the
State Council of China.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1996, we have met six times to discuss detailed
arrangements for the Annual Meetings. The discussions are very
helpful," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Seeing is believing," Ng said. "The meetings will bring an
opportunity for guests from around the world to see with their own
eyes that 'one country, two systems' is working well in Hong
Kong, Hong Kong and the Chinese inland areas are cooperating
well, and Hong Kong continues to be a leading international
business and financial center."
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong would benefit from the Meetings in a long
run. Local hotels and tourism industry will benefit immediately
from the huge number of visitors flooding in.
</P>
<P>
Ng was confident that the expenditure for the whole event would
be well controlled within the budget of 485 million HK dollars
(62.5 million U.S. dollars). A total of 70 million HK dollars
(nine million U.S. dollars) of sponsorship has been
secured. 
</P>
