<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Symposium on Nuclear Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Scholars from the United
States, Canada and China discussed the latest developments in
nuclear medicine at a two-day symposium that closed here today.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, sponsored by a nuclear medicine branch of the
Chinese Medical Association, concerned the potential of nuclear
medicine in treating heart and brain diseases and tumors, the
major killers in the world today. Its important role in treating
diseases of the urinary tract was also stressed.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear medicine began to be used in clinical treatments in
the 1940s. It uses radio-nuclides and nuclear radiation in
diagnosing and treating human diseases.
</P>
<P>
Tomographic imaging is used in nuclear medicine diagnoses, with
radios-nuclides used to provide an image of the diseased area.
</P>
<P>
Also discussed were interventional nuclear medicine, the use of
synthetic peptides, and the radio-nuclide therapy for tumors.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang Shizhen, "the father of Chinese nuclear
medicine", was honorary chairman of the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Condemns Jerusalem Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua)-- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) today swiftly condemned the three suspected
suicide bombings in central Jerusalem that killed at least five
people and wounded 140 others.
</P>
<P>
The PNA also called on Israel to refrain from tightening
straggling sanctions against the Palestinians as it usually did
after every terror attack.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Minister of Higher Education Hana Ashrawi described
the bombings as a "serious blow" to the already deeply-troubled
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ashrawi added that Israel should not impose sanctions against
the Palestinians in a form of collective punishment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai ordered security
forces to reinstitute immediately the total closure of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip. David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, readily charged the PNA for not
launching a tough crackdown on terrorism and even giving "green
light" to attacks.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses reported that two or three suspected suicide bombers
blew up themselves in the bustling downtown pedestrian mall in Ben
Yahuda street at 3 p.m. local time (noon GMT).
</P>
<P>
Body parts clad with clothes were seen scattered on the street,
indicating the grave magnitude of the explosions.
</P>
<P>
The anti-Israel Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas), which
claimed responsibility for the July 30 twin suicide bombings in the
Mahane Yehuda market in the same street, has reportedly claimed
also for today's bombings.
</P>
<P>
Israeli television showed pictures of the explosion scene in
complete chaos. A large number of ambulances arrived at the site
and police and rescue workers rushed to evacuated the wounded,
many of whose bodies covered with blood, to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem police said that among the three dead, at least two
of them were suspected to be Hamas suicide bombers.
</P>
<P>
Police have sealed off the area.
</P>
<P>
There were conflicting reports over the number of explosions,
but it was believed that there occurred three explosions in
seconds apart.
</P>
<P>
This attack appeared similar to the one on July 30 in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market, barely one kilometer away from
today's bombing site, killing 17 people and wounding 170 others.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio reported that Netanyahu has canceled all his
scheduled activities in order to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
The terror attack took place just one week before the first
visit by United States Secretary of State Medeleine Albright to
the region aimed at reviving the peace process with Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel has just eased the total blockade on the Palestinian
self-rule territories early the week, which was imposed after the
July 30 bombings, to allow a limited number of Palestinians to
enter Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
