<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Hong Kong Making Last Dash Preparing for WB/IMF  Annual Meetings (1) (By Chang Kefei) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) --- Hong Kong is making a final
 sprint in its three-year marathon preparations for the 1997 World
 Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) Annual Meetings to be
held here in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Just scurrying back from an inspection at the venue -- the Hong
 Kong Convention and Exhibition Center (HKCEC) and its newly-built
 extension, Stephen Ng, head of a 100-member planning division for
 the 1997 Meetings, told Xinhua with relief: "Up to 90 percent of
the venue facilities have been completed."
</P>
<P>
Nine hundred makeshift offices, about 20 sq. m each, have been
set up at the Extension to the HKCEC within one month, said
Ng. All will be well appointed with computers, telephones and
furniture before September 10, and security checks are slated to
begin on September 12.
</P>
<P>
In addition, seven convention and exhibition halls, two
theaters and 56 meeting rooms will be put into use before and
during the Annual Meetings, scheduled for September 23 and 25.
</P>
<P>
Venue is the hardest nut to crack for Stephen Ng since the Hong
 Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) government has no
official conference centers or hotels of its own and has to hire
them from private owners.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 major meetings, seminars, keynote sessions and
social events will be staged at the venue during the 10-day period
 starting on September 16.
</P>
<P>
Ng, an official of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA),
leads a variety al of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA),
arrangements for the meetings, ranging from venue facilities to
communications systems and to hotel accommodations,
transportation, security, airport reception, registration, social
events and cultural programs.
</P>
<P>
Security is the top priority for the most prestigious annual
event in the international financial community, which is expected
to draw 14,000 participants from more than 180 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that a bar-code system, in which computers are
installed to spot forged or stolen badges, will be used for the
first time at the entrance to the Annual Meetings'
venue. Accordingly, Hong Kong police have drawn out detailed plans
to tighten security both inside and outside the venue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
