<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Increase Trade And Economic Ties With Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Wu Yi, China's Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, speaking at a conference
on Sino-African trade and economy today, said that China plans to
strengthen trade and economic ties with Africa in various ways.
</P>
<P>
She said that China views Africa as a new market with vitality
and will make a greater effort to explore it, while sticking to a
market strategy.
</P>
<P>
From a strategic perspective, Wu said, China should make full
use of Africa's natural resources and market potential to promote
bilateral trade and economic relations and improve overall
relations.
</P>
<P>
In addition to other assistance, China will increase
co-operation in trade, contract projects, labor services, and
investment, she said, adding that the African market should be
thoroughly explored, and full use be made of enterprises and
governmental and non-governmental connections.
</P>
<P>
China and Africa haven't seen any large-scale trade or economic
co-operation, she said, but since 1991, bilateral trade ties have
improved and in 1996 there was record trade worth 4 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Trade has shifted to contract projects, labor services, and
investment, helping Sino-African trade and economic relations, Wu
said. And from now on, China will offer government loans to expand
aid to Africa, encourage joint ventures and co-operative
companies, and combine aid with investment, trade and other forms
of mutually beneficial co-operation.
</P>
<P>
From 1979 to the first six months of this year, Chinese
companies have signed 8.8 billion US dollars worth of contracts
with African companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Ecology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
called for increased afforestation and environmental improvements
that follow instructions President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li
Peng gave recently.
</P>
<P>
China's Wednesday papers published the full text of those
instructions, which called for long-term afforestation and
anti-desertification efforts.
</P>
<P>
At a forum in Beijing today, Chen Yaobang, the forestry
minister and deputy director of the National Greening Committee
(NGC), said the instructions were "mobilization orders from the
third generation of China's collective leadership with Jiang Zemin
at the core."
</P>
<P>
"These instructions ask the whole Chinese Communist Party and
the people of the whole country to go all out to improve China's
ecology and environment and for sustainable development in the new
historical period," he said.
</P>
<P>
China suffers from some of the worst environmental problems,
the minister said, and CPC leaders have attached a great deal of
importance to afforestation and improving the ecology.
</P>
<P>
"In 1991, President Jiang urged all Party members and the
Chinese people to take part in the nationwide tree-planting
campaign to green the country," he noted, and after years of
effort, China has scored great success.
</P>
<P>
"At present, attention should be paid to improving the
environment along the country's two major rivers, the Yellow and
the Yangtze, and in regions hit by wind and desertification
problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale afforestation project in many river basins,
provinces, and regions will have an effect on the country's
environment in the next century, he added.
</P>
<P>
The forum was held by the NGC and the Propaganda Department of
the Party Central Committee at the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from the ministries of Finance and
Agriculture, the State Science and Technology Commission, and
various departments were present. It was presided over by Xu
Guangchun, deputy head of the Propaganda Department of the Party
Central Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
