<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Retail trade figures released
today diminished market hopes for a near-term cut in official
interest rates, causing the Australian dollar to strengthen and
close just shy of 73 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended in Sydney at 72.96 U.S. cents, up from
72.72 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Halmarick, NatWest Markets Australia's currency
strategist, said the Australian dollar rallied particularly
strongly after the retail trade data, but then settled back around
the 73 U.S. cent level.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics figures showed Australia's
retail trade rose 2.6 percent in July to 11.155 billion Australian
dollars (8.143 billion U.S. dollars), seasonally adjusted, from a
revised 10.873 billion Australian dollars (7.937 billion U.S.
dollars) in June.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended in Sydney at 88.24 Japanese yen,
from 88.25 yesterday. Against the Deutsche mark, it was 1.3246,
from 1.3370.  
</P>
</TEXT>
