<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Progress in WTO Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan issued a joint
statement today on China's entry into the World Trade Organization
(WTO) and the substantial progress they have made in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the heads of the two countries'
negotiating delegations, concerned bilateral negotiations in Tokyo
from August 27 to 29 and in Beijing from September 2 to 3.
</P>
<P>
It said that the two sides concluded negotiations on tariff and
non-tariff measures and on standards and the attestation system of
commodities, and reached an overall framework agreement on market
access to merchandise trade.
</P>
<P>
The two sides decided to speed up efforts to reach a
satisfactory conclusion on service trade as soon as possible, and
said that progress in these negotiations will further increase the
existing solid and strong friendly relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
They also reiterated that they will co-operate closely in
negotiations with the working group in Geneva to facilitate as
early an entry as possible for China into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
After the statement was issued in Beijing today, the head of the
Chinese delegation, Long Yongtu, told reporters that China's entry
into the WTO requires agreement on market access by China and all
its trade partners, in addition to the multi-lateral negotiations
in Geneva, which are looking for a commitment by China to observe
accepted international norms.
</P>
<P>
Because Japan is China's biggest trade partner, Long noted,
conclusion of this negotiation between China and Japan on market
access to merchandise trade is significant and will propel the
process of multi-lateral negotiations on China's entry into the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China is ready to follow a flexible and
practical principle which is reciprocal and on an equal footing to
continue negotiations with other countries, in order to reach
agreements with them as early as possible on the basis of a
balance between rights and obligations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- A federal jury convicted Governor Fife Symington of Arizona
of seven felony counts of defrauding his lenders as a commercial
real estate developer, forcing his resignation from office and
leaving him facing the prospect of prison and hundreds of
thousands of dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton interrupted his vacation to appear at an
elementary school on Martha's Vineyard and promote his plan for
voluntary tests to measure pupils' performance against new
national standards in reading and math.
</P>
<P>
