<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Fell to Another Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso fell today
by 2.2 percent to another record low of 32.309 to the U.S. dollar
after the central bank decided to reduce the liquidity reserve
rate.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate went down to an all-time low of 32.43 pesos
against the dollar around midday. The volume of the transactions
reached 150 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was another setback for the peso which closed at 31.617 to
the dollar on Wednesday due to speculation arising from the
Central Bank's decision to cut the liquidity reserve rate from
eight to six percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the demand for dollars from importers and firms
with foreign exchange loans, the absence of supply coming from
portfolio investments and the slowdown of the country's economy
also fueled the fall of the peso.
</P>
<P>
Portfolio funds invested in the stock market have been flown
out of the country due to the unstable economic situation,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Economic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito announced on
Wednesday for the first time that the country would not meet its
seven-percent economic target for the year.
</P>
<P>
The economy, as measured by the gross national product, slowed
down to 5.9 percent in the first half of the year compared with
the 7.5 percent recorded in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The peso has devalued by 23 percent since the Central Bank
allowed it to float within a wider range on July 11.  
</P>
</TEXT>
