<HEADLINE> Egypt Faces Thailand in U-17 World Cup Opening Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Surprise is expected tonight as
the Egyptian national under-17 team meets its Thai counterpart
here this evening in the opening match of the world championship
for the FIFA/JVC Cup.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians will play on their own turf in the 76,000-seat
Cairo-stadium to the pride of millions of home fans. However,
tough competitions in the Group A come from Oman, Germany and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
But Thailand, reputed to be one of the dark horses in the
tournament that runs until September 21, seems to be fierce,
strong and distinguished as well.
</P>
<P>
Technical manager of the Thai team said that his boys did not
come here only to participate, but to win the match and return
home with the cup.
</P>
<P>
He added that he expects the opening match to be a surprise to
everyone, though he knows that the Egyptian team is equally strong
and one of the cup favorites.
</P>
<P>
The two teams met twice earlier before last April. At an
international tournament in Thailand, Egypt played two matches
against the host country, losing the first and winning the second.
</P>
<P>
Head coach of the Egyptian team Mohammed Ali said that the
Thais are a very strong team and plays quick football, and they
are going to be one of the surprises in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
During the team's training, the technical staff concentrated on
the two wings, and the ways to penetrate the opponent's defense
line. And in all the lectures the players have received, they
have been acknowledged with the importance of winning the first
game.
</P>
<P>
In order to decrease the stress, the players were allowed to
enjoy a movie and a rich dinner after every training course.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian team will not witness any changes in the line-up
which represented Egypt in the last encounters it played, sources
close to the team told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The tournament will be broadcast to an estimated 450 million
viewers in more than 70 countries and regions, a drastic increase
over those from 1991 in Italy, where it was aired to only 44
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Participating in this international event will be 16 teams,
representing all six football federations. They will be divied
into four groups of four playing in four cities, with the top two
from each group moving into the quarter-finals. An unprecedented
80 teams competed for one of the 16 slots.
</P>
<P>
Egypt won the coveted bid last May following a heated battle
with New Zealand to host this competition, which is but the first
of many such events to which it want to play host.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first time that this tournament take place in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
FIFA President Jaoa Havelange said earlier that the 1997 event
in Egypt will be "as good as its predecessors." He also predicted
that given the Egyptian team's strong performance in the African
Nations Cup," it could secure, if not first place, then at least
one of the top four slots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
