<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Stock Exchange Urges Solution to Market Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
(PSE) today recommended possible measures to arrest the sharp
decline of the country's stock market.
</P>
<P>
PSE President Jose Luis Yulo said that this can be effectively
done by getting government and local private funds to invest in
the bourse market, particularly when there is an outflow of
foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Despite high interest rates, some foreign funds were withdrawn
from the country due to the unstable economy, which showed signs
of a slowdown in growth in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
For various reasons, the composite index of the Philippine
Stock Exchange has fallen by 20 percent to around 2,000 points,
from 2511.5 on July 11, when the central bank announced the free
float of the Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
Yulo said that at present local investors account for only 1
percent of the investments at the exchange, compared with 20
percent in other countries.
</P>
<P>
He said possible equities that could be tapped include the
Government Service Insurance System, the Social Security System
and other private funds.
</P>
<P>
These markets should be mobilized with a mechanism that will
enable and encourage them to buy shares whenever foreign funds are
selling in substantial amounts that may result in a sharp decline
in the market, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested the development of funds from the local
retail investors and commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
"Similarly, banks should be allowed to hold stocks as part of
their reserve requirements, rather than just treasury bills which
have no real underlying value that creates wealth like what an
enterprise does," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yulo noted that taxes on stock transactions should
also be reduced back to 0.25 percent, saying documentary stamp tax
should be eliminated since the PSE is now on scripless trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
