<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Allow Further Fall of Peso: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
allow the peso to fall further rather than risk killing the
economy with high interest rates, Socioeconomic Planning Secretary
Cielito Habito said today.
</P>
<P>
Habito, who is also chief of the National Economic Development
Authority (NEDA), told reporters that opting for a peso
depreciation would be the "lesser evil" compared to high interest
rates that the central bank imposed to boost the peso value.
</P>
<P>
A higher exchange rate will have some negative impact in the
short term, but its mid-term effect can be positive since it can
create more jobs, especially in the export and import substituting
production sectors, Habito said.
</P>
<P>
But he added that higher interest rates will immediately
inhibit investments as it will be more difficult for new
businesses to obtain capital and even existing businesses to
invest more.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to prevent the peso from speculative attacks, the
central bank moved last month to keep its overnight lending rate
at as high as 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the central bank also lowered its overnight
borrowing rate to 14 percent from a record-high of 32 percent, but
it hiked banks' liquidity reserves requirement to a five-year high
of 8 percent in order to siphon off excess liquidity in the
monetary system.
</P>
<P>
However, under the pressure of bankers and businessmen, the
central bank reduced the liquidity reserves requirement by one
percentage point Wednesday. The banking and business sectors
accused the monetary authority of sacrificing the economy for a
strong peso.
</P>
<P>
In the local currency market, the peso fell to a new low of
32.30 pesos to the U.S. dollar today, a surprising 22.3-percent
fall in its value since it was allowed to float in a wider band on
July 11, resulting in the de factor depreciation of the local
currency.
</P>
<P>
Habito said the peso depreciation should not be regarded as a
"bad thing" as it is a natural consequence of the so-called
"regional currency turmoil."
</P>
<P>
But he said prime lending rates should be allowed to drop to 12
to 13 percent or the level before July 11 "to sustain the momentum
that we have already built in the last few years."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Habito said the government will have to revise
down its economic growth target because of the peso devaluation
and high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
According to Habito, President Fidel Ramos will convene an
emergency government meeting Friday to seek ways to cope with the
currency crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
