<HEADLINE> Scotland Yard Sleuths in Paris on Diana Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- An unspecified number of agents
from the Scotland Yard, the headquarters of the London
Metropolitan Police, arrived in Paris today as ``observers'' in
the on-going investigation into the car crash which killed the
Princess of Wales last Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Agence France-Presse quoted police sources as saying that the
British agents met with French Criminal Brigade anti-riot police
officers and Judge Herve Stephan of the Paris Investigation Court,
who is in charge of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Judge Stephan Tuesday decided to put under judicial inquiry six
photographers and one motorcyclist for ``involuntary homicide and
involuntary injury'' and ``non-assistance to persons in danger.''
</P>
<P>
These photographers were blamed for chasing Diana on speeding
motorcycles after she and her boyfriend, Egyptian billionaire Dodi
Al Fayed, who was also killed in the crash, left the Ritz Hotel in
central Paris.
</P>
<P>
But one of the photographers, award-winning Jacques Langevin of
the Sygma agency, denied that he had participated in the chase and
said he arrived at the scene of the accident in Alma tunnel all by
accident.
</P>
<P>
Some photographers who did chase Diana that night but got away
from police were found to have sold their tapes and photos to
foreign television companies and press publishers.
</P>
<P>
Some French photographer and press groups have protested
against the legal action against the photographers who, they said,
had become scapegoats in the accident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
