<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Chief Defends Remarks on Euro Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- German central bank president
Hans Tietmeyer Today defended his comments about the Euro made on
Wednesday, saying his remarks were not an argument in favour of a
delay.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before the central bank, Tietmeyer said
his comments to the weekly newspaper Die Woche on Wednesday only
meant to question what he thought to be some problems about the
startup of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were "clearly not an argument for postponing the
European Monetary Union", he insisted.
</P>
<P>
It would risk the confidence in a future common European
currency if people just talked about the number of countries which
would join in, but not the adherence to the qualification
criteria, Tietmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer was quoted by Die Woche on Wednesday as saying that
postponing the launch of the Euro from its scheduled date of
January 1, 1999 would not be a political or economic catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
"I simply cannot follow some arguments which I've heard
recently that in case of a delay of the Euro the sky would fall in
over Europe, or that the economy would fall apart," he told Die
Woche.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank president's remarks stirred up controversies
not only in Germany but also among European capitals. A Bonn
spokesman quickly stated on Wednesday that "the German
government is not having any debate" about delaying the Euro.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel today also gave a talk to
quell speculations that Bonn was now in favor of delaying the
Euro. He said any delay of the starting date for the European
Monetary Union (EMU) could mean the death of the entire project.
</P>
<P>
"The Euro must and will come punctually on January 1, 1999,
with strict adherence to the criteria agreed at Maastricht," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer's remarks come amid rising doubts over whether key
countries in the E.U., including Germany and France, would be able
to meet the fiscal criteria this year to qualify for the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht Treaty, countries wishing to join the Euro
club are required, among other things, to control their budget
deficit to less than three percent, and keep the overall national
debt below 60 percent of the gross domestic product. The first
wave of countries to join the EMU will be chosen in the spring of
1998, based on the EU states' full economic data in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
