<HEADLINE> Tamil Rebels Collect Taxes From Farmers In Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels are
demanding 1,000 rupees (about 17 U.S. dollars) for per acre of
land as taxes from farmers during this year's major paddy harvest
season in Batticaloa District of Eastern province, informed
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Farmers who normally lease the land from landlords said that if
they pay this tax to the rebels they would be unable to pay
anything to the land owners, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war for a
separate Tamil state in the north and east of the country since
1983.
</P>
<P>
The major cultivation season in the district has just begun.
There are about 10,000 acres of land under cultivation in the area
and It is feared that less than half of the acreage will go under
the plough this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
