<HEADLINE> Regional Strategy Being Drawn Up to Counter Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and other
countries in the region are working out a collective strategy to
counter the attacks mounted by international syndicates on
regional economies particularly the share markets and currencies.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here today by Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim, who described the current developments in
the region as an "economic war" waged by Western syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The Western syndicates are using the ASEAN's weakness in
defending its economies from attack as a weapon to wage lightning
raids, Anwar, who is also finance minister, told the joint opening
of the general assemblies of the Women Wing and Youth Wing of the
ruling United Malays National Organization.
</P>
<P>
He observed that even though the ASEAN is seen as "united"
economically, the economic interests of each member nation still
supersede the interests of the region as there is still
competition among ASEAN countries either conspicuously or
inconspicuously.
</P>
<P>
The attackers are aware of this weakness and their strategy now
is to launch sudden attacks against these countries one by one, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the consequences arising from the attack on the Thai
economy were not quickly seen as a smooth strategy by these
syndicates until Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore were also
affected.
</P>
<P>
The financial tumble in Thailand has affected all ASEAN
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
