<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some 300,000 Facing Starvation in Papua New Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Up to 300,000 Papua New
Guineans are facing starvation due to a drought caused by the El
Nino weather pattern, which a Papua New Guinea (PNG) official
expects to last until the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The worst-hit areas are the highlands provinces of Enga,
Southern Highlands and Western Highlands, PNG National Disaster
and Emergency Services Director Leith Anderson was quoted by the
Australian Associated Press (AAP) as saying today.
</P>
<P>
The maritime provinces, which were devastated by Cyclone Justin
earlier this year, have also been hit by water shortages.
</P>
<P>
Milne Bay Province on the southeastern coast is being forced to
transport water from other areas, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
The drought has also led to the closure of the OK Tedi copper
mine in Western Province due to low water levels in the Fly River
stranding supply and transport vessels. Production at the Porgera
gold mine has also been slowed by the conditions.
</P>
<P>
Anderson said El Nino has caused the worst drought in 50 years,
with no sign of it abating.
</P>
<P>
"The El Nino forecast is looking pretty bleak for another three
to four months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The problem of food gardens being affected by the drought has
been compounded by recent frosts in the highlands, the official
said.
</P>
<P>
PNG Prime Minister Bill Skate has announced a 2.73 million U.S.
dollar assistance package to help the drought-affected provinces.
</P>
<P>
He said 300,000 people there are facing starvation, schools are
closed and there is a danger of a breakdown in health services.
</P>
<P>
PNG is not the only country suffering from El Nino in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Part of Australia has been under the influence of the El Nino
weather pattern, a recent world weather conference in Geneva has
revealed. Australian experts have also confirmed some parts of
their country are being affected by the weather pattern.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
