<HEADLINE> Australian Youth Jobless Rate Third Highest in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- About 28 percent of
Australian youth were jobless, ranking third in the world,
Australian Federal Training Minister David Kemp said today.
</P>
<P>
"It (youth unemployment) is a problem which is very serious in
international terms .... If you calculate youth unemployment as a
percentage of the total 15-24 year-old age group, Australia still
has the third highest youth unemployment in the world," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"That is a very disturbing fact and one that we should not in
any way seek to minimize," Kemp said when launching a campaign to
encourage employers to hire more youngsters.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, did not name the two countries with the
highest youth unemployment in the world.
</P>
<P>
"In Australia I believe we have become far too fatalistic about
youth unemployment," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We can't have a situation such as the one we've got at the
moment where some 25 percent of young people aged 24 who left
school early and haven't taken any further training, have not had
a year's continuous employment since they left school. That is
just an intolerable situation which damages the lives of those
young people."
</P>
<P>
Two programs have been launched nationwide recently to help
jobless youth get training or to spread a message across Australia
to employers to hire more young people.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show youth unemployment reached 27.9 percent
in July, compared to the 8.7 percent jobless rate for older people
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment has remained high for the past decade and one of
the major domestic issues in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Australian federal government has said recently that the
jobless rate will fall as the economy has been improving with
lower inflation and interest rates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
