<HEADLINE> HK New Airport's Lighting Designed for Worst Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The newly-installed runway
lighting system at Hong Kong's new airport would enable the Chek
Lap Kok facility to be operational 24 hours a day even when
visibility is at its worst, according to the Airport Authority.
</P>
<P>
Senior construction engineer Michael Collishaw said Wednesday
that the 163 million HK dollars multi-colored system has been
installed at the world's most advanced airports including Denver,
Heathrow and Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The system has a number of safety features, according to
local English-language newspaper Hong Kong Standard.
</P>
<P>
Should an aircraft approach the runway too high or too low,
indicators on either side would flash white or red respectively,
warning the pilot to abort landing.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the system allows the runway to operate even
during very foggy conditions with horizontal visibility of less
than 200 meters and vertical visibility of less than 30 meters,
the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Authority estimated that more than 80 movements per
 hour could be handled by the two runways, more than double the
existing capacity of Kai Tak airport which handles 31 movements
her hour.
</P>
<P>
The southern runway was completed while the northern runway
would be in use by November next year, according to corporate
development director Clinton Leeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
