<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin to Send Envoy to Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
will dispatch a special envoy to the Middle East within the next
few days on a fresh mission to restore the peace march to its
right track, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the presidential envoy falls as part of Russia's
position as co-sponsor in the Mideast peace process that was
initiated with Madrid, MENA quoted a Russian high-ranking official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Valeri Kosmain, deputy chairman of the Middle East and North
Africa department at the Russian Foreign Ministry, made the
statement on the sidelines of the ongoing seminar on the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Russian diplomat said that the return of the Russian envoy
to the region came within the context of recent intensive
diplomatic contacts by various parties concerned to get the peace
process off hook.
</P>
<P>
Victor Visselev, the presidential envoy, will hold intensive
contacts during his multi-leg tour to the region, Kosmain said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia is keen on participating in the various diplomatic
efforts toward the activation of the peace march not only on the
Palestinian-Israeli track but also on the Syrian and Lebanese
ones," said the diplomat.
</P>
<P>
But this does not mean that they should be reactivated at the
same time, he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had received a message from Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov on Moscow's role in the troubled peace process,
which started under the co-sponsorship of Washington and Moscow in
1991.
</P>
<P>
The Russian mission is coincided with a high-profile trip by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to the region this
month. She is expected to bring a major U.S. initiative to revive
the peace process that collapsed in March when Israel broke ground
for a new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In the past months, Russia has significantly lowered its
mediating profile and the United States was much criticized for
being "too passive" in breaking the impasse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
