<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA To Defray U-17 World Cup Cost Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Football
Federation (FIFA) has agreed to compensate Egypt for the huge gap
between costs and revenues of Under-17 Soccer World Championship
being hosted by the African country.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Executive Body of the Egyptian Higher Council of
Youth and Sports Abdel Menem Emara, said today that he expects the
revenues of the U-17 World Cup to reach three million Egyptian
pounds, acquired in ticket sales and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
But the cost for organizing this championship, which begins
here today and runs throughout September 21, amounted to seven
million pounds.
</P>
<P>
He said the actual fees could be much higher though total cost
will not be made available until the ten-day games are finalized.
</P>
<P>
"FIFA has promised to compensate for the difference between
revenues and costs to lift the financial burden off Egypt," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The tournament will be broadcast to an estimated 450 million
viewers in more than 70 countries and regions. This figure is a
drastic increase over those from 1991 in Italy, where it was aired
to only 44 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Participating in this international event will be 16 teams,
representing all six football federations. They will be divided
into four groups of four, with the top two from each group moving
into the quarter-finals. An unprecedented 80 teams competed for
one of the 16 slots.
</P>
<P>
Egypt won the coveted bid last May following a heated battle
with New Zealand to host this competition.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that this tournament take place in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Emara said, is capable of organizing the world soccer
championship for adults, especially after FIFA officials have
extolled its arrangements and preparations for the championship.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has a solid and gigantic sports infrastructure that
provides it with great capabilities for hosting such
championships," he added.
</P>
<P>
FIFA President Jaoa Havelange is very supportive of Egypt's
capabilities and has the desire to have an African country host
the world soccer championship for adults, said the Egyptian
official.
</P>
<P>
Havelange said earlier that the 1997 event in Egypt will be "as
good as its predecessors." He also predicted that given the
Egyptian team's strong performance in the African Nations Cup," it
could secure, if not first place, then at least one of the top
four slots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
