<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qagano Defends Short Downhill Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Organizers for the Nagano
Olympic Winter Games defended on Thursday their decision to stage
the shortest ever Olympic men's downhill next February.
</P>
<P>
"The International Olympic Committee and Inernational Ski
Federation understood our position," Nagano director general
Makoto Kobayashi said.
</P>
<P>
"If the starting point had been raised the Nagano Games would
have been labeled the Games which destroyed nature," he added.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists had objected to the downhill race -- the blue
ribband event of Alpine skiing -- starting higher than 1,680
meters.
</P>
<P>
Kobayashi pointed out they had never hidden the length of the
race, which will take under two minutes to ski.
</P>
<P>
"It was in our bid document," he said. Nagano won the right to
stage the Games in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But the ski federation had asked if the start could not be
raised to 1,800 meters.
</P>
<P>
Kobayashi also said they had asked Japan Railways to lay on
additional trains after 10pm to take spectators back to Tokyo
after late night events.
</P>
<P>
The bullet train, which will cut travelling time between Tokyo
and Nagano from four hours to 67 minutes, will start operating in
October.
</P>
<P>
A record 82 countries and regions -- up from 67 at Lillehammer
in 1994 -- will compete at Nagano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
