<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy: Tung's U.S. Trip to Further HK-U.S. Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. official said here
today that the forthcoming visit of Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, to the United
States would further the trade-economic relations between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
The important talks Tung will have with U.S. government
officials at the highest levels will "solidify the pattern and
pace of our future relationship," Consul-General Richard Boucher
said in an address at the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Officials in Washington welcome his visit and look forward to
discussing the numerous issues which influence the ties between
Hong Kong and the United States," the senior U.S. diplomat said.
"I feel confident that those talks will establish a friendly and
solid working relationship that will carry us into the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
Tung is to arrive in the United States in a few days.
</P>
<P>
Boucher pointed out that the last American Chamber of Commerce
survey conducted before the July 1 handover showed that U.S.
business people here were overwhelmingly optimistic about Hong
Kong's commercial future.
</P>
<P>
"I might note that American interests in Hong Kong are
essentially the same today as they were before July 1: economic
and commercial involvement, law enforcement cooperation, U.S. Navy
port calls, and cultural and educational ties -- only more so," he
continued. "If anything, our interests have grown in recent
months."
</P>
<P>
According to Boucher, about 50,000 U.S. citizens now live in
Hong Kong. This means the American community here has doubled over
the past five years, he said, adding that U.S. "investment (here)
is also up."
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. consul-general pointed out, there also exist
a number of issues between the two sides and they need to be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking for success in Hong Kong's efforts against the
theft of intellectual property," Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that software and video piracy not only harms
American exporters but steals from the legitimate earnings of Hong
Kong creative artists and singers and sets back Hong Kong's
aspirations to become a high-technology center.
</P>
<P>
"We also want to engage Hong Kong in the international fight
against money laundering, a crime which is naturally attracted to
one of the world's great financial centers," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong continues to be an important international hub and a
base for the development of international trading institutions,
Boucher said, noting that Hong Kong is a dynamic city which needs
to develop.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that "Hong Kong will remain the dynamic,
flexible catalyst for change which it has been in the past, and
that it will continue to change in the direction that Hong Kong
people have set for themselves, within the excellent framework of
the Basic Law and the (Sino-British) Joint Declaration."  
</P>
</TEXT>
