<HEADLINE> No Golf Competition at Sydney Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Sydney Olympic Games
Organising Committee president Michael Knight said Thursday that
there would be no golf competitions for the 2000 games.
</P>
<P>
"The programme is closed. We cannot take on any more sports,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
International Olympic Committee sports director Gilbert Felli
had said on Monday IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch was
prepared to raise the question with the United States and
European PGAs at the Ryder Cup in Spain at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
The Games programme will comprise 290 events, up from 271 at
Atlanta, spread across 28 sports.
</P>
<P>
Sydney, determined to stick to a maximum 10,200 participants
for the Games, has already agreed to reinsert four canoe-kayak
slalom events alongside two trampoline events incorporated into
the gymnastics timetable.
</P>
<P>
There is also to be a women's water-polo tournament, provided
the International Swimming Federation FINA gives its approval.
</P>
<P>
Knight revealed that more fans would have the chance to get to
events at Sydney following approval by the IOC of several venue
changes.
</P>
<P>
Another 176,000 tickets will be available after changes for
basketball, boxing, fencing, handball and volleyball.
</P>
<P>
This is in addition to another 144,000 seats provided by kayak
slalom (60, 000), trampolining (60,000) and possibly women's water
polo (24,000). 
</P>
