<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Chief Urges Nigerians to Quit S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The west African peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) which is to enforce an embargo on Sierra Leone has
urged Nigerians in that troubled country to leave.
</P>
<P>
"Total economic blockade will result in cries and hues. Those
who have families there should advise their relations to return
home," said ECOMOG Force Commander Major-General Victor Malu
Wednesday, quoted by press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Economic sanctions and embargo aimed to flush out Sierra
Leone's military junta which seized power in a coup in May were
ordered by the just-concluded summit of the Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone and the imperative for military action to
dislodge the junta led by Major Johnny Koroma dominated the 20th
ECOWAS summit which ended last week in Abjua, capital of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The junta has not yet made formal response to the resolution
passed at the summit.
</P>
<P>
But Malu said if the coup leaders fired any shot at the
peace-keeping force, there would be bloody retaliation.
</P>
<P>
"My men will return fire for fire if the lives of my men are
threatened," said Malu, who left here for ECOMOG headquarters in
Monrovia, capital of Liberia, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were sent to Sierra Leone in the wake of the
coup and have reportedly clashes with soldiers loyal to the junta
for several times.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Nigeria accused the junta of violating the
sub-regional resolution on the country by planning to launch
attack against ECOMOG troops in Freetown, the Sierra Leonean
capital.
</P>
<P>
"The planned attack on ECOMOG positions will be carried out
within 24 hours," said a statement issued by Nigeria's Defense
Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States has reiterated its willingness to
work with ECOWAS to resolve the political crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In a statement faxed to the News Agency of Nigeria in Abuja on
Wednesday, the U.S. Information Service said: "We look forward to
working with ECOWAS to help resolve peacefully regional issues of
mutual concern such as the crisis in Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
It added that the gesture was in furtherance of the
cooperation demonstrated with the sub-region in the resolution of
the Liberian crisis which resulted in the restoration of
democracy last month after seven years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The statement praised ECOMOG for its contribution to the end
of factional fightings in Liberia, adding that "ECOWAS can take
pride in this achievement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
