<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Reduce Car Duty, Increase Cigarette </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government has
decided to reduce the duty on imported cars and increase 10
percent tax on imported tobacco, Lebanese newspaper Beirut
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced after a weekly cabinet session
Wednesday by Lebanese Information Minister Bassem Sabaa.
</P>
<P>
Sabaa told reporters that the new duties will make imported
cars costing up to 20 million Lebanese liras (about 13,000
U.S. dollars) to carry a 20 percent duty, those between 20
million to 60 million liras (about 39,000 U.S. dollars) at 50
percent, and those above 60 million liras at 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government's original June measures set duties on cars
costing between 15 million liras (about 9,000 U.S. dollars) and
50 million liras (about 32,000 U.S.dollars) at 50 percent, rising
to 100 percent for the 50 million liras to 100 million liras
(about 64,000) price range, while the duty on luxury cars costing
100 million liras or more was set at 200 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sabaa said after the tax increase, the rate on imported
cigarettes will reach 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the moves came as part of the governmental
efforts to collect revenues to finance the rural development
projects and the repatriation of Lebanese refugees who had been
displaced during the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
