<HEADLINE> Drug-Carrying Ship Barred from Docking in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan authorities have
foiled an attempt by a ship suspected to be carrying over 30 tons
of hashish to offload its cargo in the country's southern beach,
the East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
It could have been the largest cargo of hashish ever landed on
the Kenyan coast, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The ship, which was believed to try to find a suitable landing
ground for its drug along the south coast beach of Majoreni,
retreated to international waters last weekend when it saw Kenyan
Navy and anti-narcotics police waiting, said the report.
</P>
<P>
A senior governmental official confirmed the news and said the
ship remained in international waters until Sunday when it sailed
away.
</P>
<P>
The ship was first sighted in the high seas on August 26 while
at the same time a suspected Mombasa drug baron was seen driving
around the beaches where he allegedly made several stop-overs for
hashish trafficking.
</P>
<P>
An anti-narcotics team, together with the Kenyan Navy and
Kenya Wildlife Service, are pursuing the ship currently,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The whole of the Coast from Lamu Island to Vanga is now under
surveillance to ensure the ship does not anchor. 
</P>
