<HEADLINE> Kenyan Ruling Party to Hold National Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 4 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) will hold its National Delegates Conference
on September 16 expectedly over constitutional reforms talks with
the Opposition ahead of the general elections.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi is to chair the conference, which
will be attended by 12 delegates from each constituency and 24
delegates from each district, KANU Secretary-General Joseph
Kamotho was quoted by today's "East African Standard" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The National Executive Council (NEC) and the National
Governing Council (NGC), the leadership of KANU, will have
meetings a day earlier, said the press report.
</P>
<P>
KANU's annual delegates conference in 1992 nominated Moi as
sole presidential candidate for the ruling party in the first
multi-party general elections.
</P>
<P>
Political atmosphere is tightening in the eastern African
country, facing the second general elections following the
suspension of key aid package by the International Monetary Fund
and recent killings in Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Moi, aged 73 and in power since 1978, has recently claimed for
times that he would announce the poll date soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
