<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Satisfied With Accord With Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) has expressed satisfaction with a
three-point agreement it signed with the Philippine government,
the Philippine News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, said
the rebels hope the agreement, which was seen as the key to their
formal peace negotiations with the government, will facilitate the
return of war evacuees to their respective places in Central
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
They also consider the agreement vital to the normalization of
peace and order in the region, the agency quoted Jaafar as saying.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by the joint government and MILF
sub-committee on cessation of hostilities Wednesday after a
two-day meeting in Cotabato City, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
It provides for the gradual repositioning of government troops
in Pikit, the southern province of Cotabato, to their positions
before June 16, when a month-long battle between the military and
MILF broke out.
</P>
<P>
It also contains provisions for the safe return of rebels who
reside in civilian villages provided they will not establish
outposts and display firearms and for the enforcement of law by
police with close coordination from MILF liaison offices in those
areas.
</P>
<P>
"If the agreement is implemented, I don't see any reason why
the evacuees will not return to their homes," Jaafar said.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the two sides failed to create a
mechanism that will ensure the implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
In their two-day meeting, the two parties again failed to
discuss the ground rules for a general cease-fire agreement for
which the meeting was called.
</P>
<P>
But Jaafar explained that the negotiators intentionally set
aside the matters regarding the truce as the concern for the safe
return of evacuees to their places of origin was deemed more
immediate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
