<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Energy Cooperation Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
called for the submission of energy projects eligible for
co-financing under an international cooperation program.
</P>
<P>
The EU move, through the regional alliance's executive body,
the European Commission, is also designed to boost cooperation
with non-EU member countries, media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Through the Synergy energy cooperation program, which was
recently rolled over for 1997, the EU aims to secure energy supply
and achieve global competitiveness and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Apart from projects launched by EU nations, the program also
provides financial aid for projects initiated by non-EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member EU may contribute up to 50 percent of the total
cost of a selected project, which will not exceed 300,000 European
Currency Units (ECU), equivalent to about 390,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Projects may be submitted by specialized international and
regional organizations, national energy ministries, committees,
companies, financial institutions and other related organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Synergy program is due to run till the end of the year on a
temporary basis, pending adoption of the EU's medium-term
financial perspectives for the post-1999 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
