<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Declining Green Peacock Population (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China's green peacock
population has dropped to around 1,000, according to a recent
investigation conducted in southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The investigation, the first of its kind in the world, revealed
that Yunnan, the reputed "Home of Peacocks," is currently home to
between 800-1,000 peacocks.
</P>
<P>
Now, there are two species of peacocks worldwide -- blue and
green -- with the Chinese habitat of latter in southern, western
and central parts of Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents indicate that peacocks thrived in vast
areas south of the Yangtze River in ancient times, but are
currently found only in Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
The peacock population has dropped dramatically since the 1970s
despite the fact that the birds have been placed under first-class
state protection. The green peacock is, in fact, classified as one
of the world's most endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Yang Lan, an ornithologist with a zoology institute in Kunming,
the capital of Yunnan Province, headed the investigation. Yang
recalled that flocks of peacock could be found throughout Yunnan
as last as the mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
"I was truly disappointed that we were unable to find the birds
in most areas during the recent investigation," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
Investigators discovered that many forests which were formerly
the habitat of peacocks have been turned into farmland.
</P>
<P>
"The destruction of the natural habitat of peacocks has greatly
reduced the range of the birds and has in turn resulted in
inbreeding which has weakened their ability to adapt to nature,"
according to Yang.
</P>
<P>
Poachers constitute another major threat to the peaceful
existence of peacocks, Yang said, adding that 11 birds were killed
in one remote county alone between 1980-1993.
</P>
<P>
Pesticides have also caused the death of a number of birds
searching for food on terraced fields.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flourishing Ethnic Unity in China  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 1 (Xinhua) -- The Danish ambassador to the
United Nation recently commented that "China's successful
experience in uniting people from all ethnic groups provides an
excellent example which can be emulated by countries with ethnic
problems."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador made the remarks during a UN seminar on ethnic
problems and ethnic policies. Participants in the seminar also
responded enthusiastically to a speech delivered by the Chinese
representative.
</P>
<P>
The close unity between the military and civilians and the
unity of various ethnic groups have ensured social stability in
China's ethnic regions.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 advanced working units in the country's ethnic
regions have received high praise for close ethnic unity, with
military units garrisoned in various regions involved in the
construction of more than 30 major projects.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic regions, which account for 64 percent of the country's
total land space, have exerted strenuous efforts since the early
1990s to expand reform and develop the market economy.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the
State Council have paid great attention to economic and social
development in the national minorities' regions, and have adopted
a series of effective measures to help narrow the gap of
development between the said regions and eastern coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
The Fifth Plenum of the Central Committee of the 14th CPC
National Congress proposed five measures to narrow the differences
between the west and east.
</P>
<P>
The nation has supported economic development in major ethnic
areas in central and western China by injecting additional capital
input and launching more projects in these regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
