<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asia's Export Growth to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Distressed by a continuous
turmoil in their financial markets, Southeast Asian nations may
feel somewhat relieved at the signs of an export recovery, which
could alleviate their pain of the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The grave impact of the crisis has already been felt by
Southeast Asian countries since their currencies and stocks began
to fall in early July.
</P>
<P>
Higher interest rates are choking corporate expansions; weaker
currencies are raising the cost of foreign debt payments;
shrinking tax revenues are restricting government spending, and
lower consumer demand is forcing multinationals to pull back their
investment from job-creating factories and distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
But until now, most currencies in the region have not stopped
falling. On Wednesday, the Philippine currency tumbled to a new
all-time low of 31.83 pesos to the U.S. dollar. Other currencies
in the region have also dropped between 10 percent to more than 20
percent in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Though steady growth is still expected in most of Southeast
Asian countries in 1997 and 1998, economic slowdowns seem
unavoidable, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Except Singapore, economists said, all other Southeast Asian
countries which are suffering from the currency crisis would see a
slower pace of their economic growth in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to their latest forecast, Malaysia's gross domestic
product (GDP) will increase by 7.8 percent this year and 7.6
percent for next year.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's GDP is expected to grow by 1.9 percent this year and
2.3 percent in 1998, while the Philippines' GDP is likely to
expand by 5.6 percent this year and 5.8 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Economists predicted a 7.4 percent GDP growth for Indonesia in
1997 and 7.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, even the slower growth rates could only be achieved by
these countries through expanding their exports. Otherwise, they
would feel much pain of the currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, signs of an export recovery are in sight, and most
countries in the region have reported faster export growth in the
past few months.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, merchandise exports increased 22 percent in
the first seven months to 13.76 billion U.S. dollars from 11.27
billion dollars a year ago. The growth rate was more robust than
the 17.3 percent recorded in the corresponding period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, whose trade drives two-thirds of its economy,
non-oil exports grew 6.9 percent in July from a year earlier,
exceeding the 5.5 percent predicted by analysts. In June,
Singapore registered its best export performance since May 1996
with a 8.8 percent increase in its non-oil exports.
</P>
<P>
Export Performance in Thailand, Indonesia and other countries
are also reportedly improving.
</P>
<P>
The improvement in the region's export performance can be
attributed to the rising global demand for electronic goods, the
major export products of Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
After a year's cyclical decline, the world's electronic market
began to show signs of a recovery in the first quarter of this
year. In the United States alone, orders for electronics and
electrical equipment rose by 12.5 percent in the first quarter
from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
The rising demand for electronic products in the world market
would paint a better picture of the region's exports this year,
and this in turn will keep the region's economy growing steadily.
</P>
<P>
Another important factor which would stimulate the region's
export this year is the de facto devaluation of Southeast Asian
nations' currencies in the last two months, as weaker currencies
have made their export products more competitive in places like
the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
This is a good news for countries in the region after they
suffered a slump in recent years as costs rose, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
After being hit by the currency crisis, Southeast Asian
countries also adopted measures to promote their exports, such as
providing low interest loans to export sectors and establishing
export-oriented joint ventures with foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
With the faster growth of exports this year, Southeast Asian
countries could be relieved of the pains of the on-going currency
crisis, analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half-Year Global Gold Demand Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Global gold demand hit a
record high of 1,493 tons in the first half of this year, up 14
percent from the corresponding period of last year, according to
statistics from the World Gold Council (WGC).
</P>
<P>
Gold demand since the start of the third quarter has stayed
strong and is expected to remain so throughout this year, an
official of the WGC's mission in Shanghai said.
</P>
<P>
He said that demand grew rapidly especially in developing Asian
countries, the Middle East, India, and Latin America, with total
gold consumption in these areas up 18 percent year-on-year between
January and June.
</P>
<P>
During the period, demand for gold rocketed 113 percent in
Turkey, 36 percent in India, 27 percent in Taiwan, compared with a
drop of five percent in the developed markets.
</P>
<P>
The WGC is a non-profit institution composed of major gold
mines worldwide. Its calculation of global gold demand accounts
for more than 80 percent of the actual need for gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
