<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drama on Ancient Reformer Wins National Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- A play recalling the history
of a reformer some 2,000 years ago won the "Wenhua Award" here
today.
</P>
<P>
The "Wenhua Award" is China's top honor for stage shows.
</P>
<P>
"Shang Yang," produced with a record investment of 800,000 yuan
(some 100,000 US dollars), is the true story of Shang Yang, an
official who promoted what are considered to be the earliest
efforts to unite and develop China.
</P>
<P>
Shang, a cabinet member of the Qin kingdom during the Warring
States period (475-221 B.C.), suggested that governance by strict
law would strengthen the country and add to its prosperity. He
also advocated the building of a powerful army and government, and
developing the economy.
</P>
<P>
His reform proved to be effective, as it laid a solid
foundation on which Emperor Qinshihuang built the Qin Dynasty and
united China for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The drama caused a sensation late last year when it was staged
in the Chinese capital city. Ordinary citizens, officials and even
central government leaders watched the performances.
</P>
<P>
Critics said that the drama, created by the Shanghai Youth
Drama Troupe, has expressed profound meanings through unique
artistic language.
</P>
<P>
Together with the drama, many other dramas, dances and operas
have won the award, which is presented by the Chinese Ministry of
Culture.
</P>
<P>
Many of them touch on the reform and opening up theme, as well
as the return of Hong Kong, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
They said that all the works were created in 1996, a
significant period when all the artists firmly abided by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's instructions on cultural development.
</P>
<P>
Some 700 plays have been given the award since it was
established in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0191 </DOCNO>
