<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Slams Albright for not Making Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 4 (Xinhua) -- More and more Lebanese
officials and politicians slammed U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright for her failure to include Lebanon in her
itinerary to the Middle East, local media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Albright's tour, which is to start next Tuesday, will include
Israel, Palestinian-held territory, Egypt, Jordan, Syria and Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese newspaper The Daily Star today quoted Lebanon's
senior Shiite cleric Sheikh Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah as saying
that Albright's exclusion of Lebanon was irrelevant, because the
sole aim of her trip was to help bolster the Israeli government
led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"Our problem with America is that it always uses its power to
try to give Israel an internationally free hand through the
crimes committed against the Palestinian people and through
aggressions against Lebanon," he said during his weekly Koranic
lecture.
</P>
<P>
At the other end of the political spectrum, the opposition
National Coalition slammed Albright's decision and emphasized
that Lebanon is an independent country and should be treated as
such.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the U.S. secretary of state to include Lebanon in
her itinerary as an important leg on her tour and to open a new
page of close relations with Lebanon as an independent and
sovereign state," the party said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Member of Parliament Butros Harb insisted that Albright
should visit Lebanon as the south is the last front-line in the
Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the visit cannot be successful, practical and
fruitful if it does not include all the countries concerned in
the Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
This will be Albright's first trip to the region since she
took office in January this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
