<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Provides Credit Facility to DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government has
approved a 161-million-Zimbabwe-Dollar credit facility (14
million US Dollars) to be extended to the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) to help it buy food from Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Minister of Industry and Commerce Nathan
Shamuyarira said here yesterday that the Zimbabwean government
would extend the credit line to the DRC to allow the two
countries to increase trade in a variety of goods, local daily
"The Herald" reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said the facility becomes effective forthwith and it would
be increased to more than 500 million Zimbabwe Dollars (43.5 US
Dollars) by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
He added a trade agreement was being negotiated and would be
signed before the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the DRC would buy goods from Zimbabwe on
credit with Zimbabwean businessmen being paid by a consortium of
seven local banks which would in turn recover their monies from
the DRC businessmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
