<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Arrives in Singapore on 1st Overseas Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, Tung Chee
Hwa, arrived here today on a three-day visit at the invitation of
Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong.
</P>
<P>
Tung flew in the Singapore Changi International Airport from
Malaysia, where he just concluded a two-day visit, his first
overseas trip since assuming office on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ow Chin Hock, Singapore minister of state for foreign
affairs, and Chinese ambassador to Singapore Chen Baoliu greeted
Tung upon his arrival at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Tung is accompanied by his wife Betty Tung and 13 senior HKSAR
government officials, including Miss Denise Yue, secretary for
trade and industry, and Dominic Wong, secretary for housing.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Tung will have meetings with Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong, Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew and Deputy
Prime Minister Tony Tan Keng Yam.
</P>
<P>
He will also be briefed on Singapore's education and public
housing policies. He will tour Toa Payoh housing estate in the
central part of Singapore and visit two families there. He will
also visit the Chinese High School.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Tung will address a distinguished audience of 400
government officials and business leaders on "Hong Kong After the
Transition" at a luncheon talk to give an update on developments
in Hong Kong since its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is one of Singapore's major trading partners. While
Singapore's total global trade grew by 5.1 percent in 1996, trade
with Hong Kong increased by a larger margin of 7.1 percent to
reach about 15 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's trade with Hong Kong for the first seven months of
this year amounted to around 9.3 billion dollars, up 10 percent
compared to the same period of last year. Meanwhile, Singapore's
accumulated investments in Hong Kong total about 4.6 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Tung and his delegation will leave Singapore on Saturday
morning for Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
