<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao Zedong's Hometown in Modern Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Shaoshan, a small village in
central China's Hunan Province, has received more than 40 million
domestic and overseas visitors eager to see the hometown of the
late Chairman Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, the first group of journalists from the former
Soviet Union rode to the remote village on horseback. Now, easy
access is afforded by road or rail.
</P>
<P>
Mao's former residence has maintained the traditional style of
Chinese village houses of the last century. But opposite it is a
restaurant bustling with noise and excitement, which is named
"Mao Jia Restaurant."
</P>
<P>
In the dining area, an air conditioner blows beside a bronze
statue of the late Chairman, one of the founding fathers of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and New China.
</P>
<P>
Tang Ruiren, owner of the restaurant, said that she has opened
13 restaurants across the country since she built the first one
ten years ago. This restaurant, whose name has been registered
with local commercial administrative authorities, receives
hundreds of tourists every day.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 100 restaurants in Shaoshan, most of them
named after the late Chairman, said village official Mao Yushi,
who has been elected deputy to the forthcoming 15th National
Congress of the CPC and will soon leave for Beijing.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 300 vendor's stalls hawking souvenirs and
small commodities in Shaoshan, which has only 400 households.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the tourists, there are also more than 700 people
from elsewhere in the country operating businesses in the
village.
</P>
<P>
The Memorial Park for Mao Zedong, which cost 46 million yuan
(about 5.5 million US dollars) and opened to visitors last year,
has to date brought in some 11 million yuan of returns, according
to the park's manager.
</P>
<P>
In today's Shaoshan, wide-screen color TV sets, air
conditioners, telephone sets and VCD players have become common
possessions of ordinary villagers.
</P>
<P>
"Each family in the village now has more money, and wants to
make their houses prettier and more comfortable," said Mao Qiman,
who has made a fortune through interior decoration. He bought a
car worth over 60,000 yuan just several months ago.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the per capita income in Shaoshan reached
5,200 yuan last year, making it one of the most prosperous
villages in central China.
</P>
<P>
A popular antithetic couplet in Shaoshan has reflected the
actual feeling of the villagers: Never forget Chairman Mao who
brought us liberation and thank Deng Xiaoping who gave us
prosperity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
