<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Airlines Not to Ground Tupolevs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 4 (Xinhua) - Vietnam Airlines said today it
will not ground Tupolev aircraft after one of its a Tu-134 plane
crashed Wednesday in Phnom Penh, killing 65 people.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the airlines said the state-run carrier will
continue to fly the four remaining Soviet-made Tupolev planes in
its fleet because all of them are within their period of
operational validity.
</P>
<P>
The Tu-134B passenger plane, which was on flight from Ho Chi
Minh City in southern Vietnam to the Cambodian capital of Phnom
Penh, crashed into paddy fields just off the airport when it was
trying to land in downpours.
</P>
<P>
An investigation has been launched into the cause of the crash,
which killed all but one aboard the ill-fated plane.
</P>
<P>
Most of the dead were foreigners including South Koreans,
Chinese, Japanese, Thais, Americans and Canadians.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's crash was the third air accident involving a Tu-134
aircraft Vietnam Airlines suffered in ten years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
