<HEADLINE> Rebel Leader Blamed for Stalled Peace in Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President General
Omar Hassan Al-Bashir has blamed the stalling of peace process in
his country on rebel leader John Garang, who was allegedly
shunning all peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia today said that the visiting Sudanese
leader appealed Wednesday to other African heads of state to help
persuade the Garang faction to step on the peace track in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Fresh efforts are underway in the war-torn country to try and
bring Garang to the roundtable, said Al-Bashir, but he did not
give details.
</P>
<P>
At the Lusaka International Airport, General Al-Bashir, who
concluded a two-day visit to Zambia, told reporters before his
departure for South Africa that "our conviction is that there is
no need for continued war in our country" following a peace
agreement drawn in Khartoum in April 1989.
</P>
<P>
Garang refused to sign the agreement, saying that it merely
served the purposes of the government, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president added that his government had
previously reached agreements with other factions except the
Garang-led Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) which was "away"
from the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He explained that some of the causes leading to the conflicts
with those in the southern Sudan included complaints of
unbalanced development, uneven distribution of national wealth
and religious misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
Since 1989 when Al-Bashir came into power, the Sudanese
government has been trying to make peace with all the
anti-government forces including the SPLA fighters, but no
progress has been made to date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
