<HEADLINE> AFL Player Suspended for Steroid Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, Australia (Xinhua) -- Australian Rules football
player Justin Charles was suspended for 16 games Thursday after he
tested positive for a banned performance-enhancing drug.
</P>
<P>
Charles, a ruckman with Australian Football League (AFL) club
Richmond, admitted he used anabolic steroid boldenone after his
positive test result in June.
</P>
<P>
The maximum suspension for drug use in the AFL is a full season
of 22 games.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time a player had been suspended for steroid
use in the 101 year-old AFL competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
