<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrillas Hold 23 Workers Hostage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A group of Colombian
guerrillas raided a hydroelectric power station in the
northwestern part of the country Wednesday, taking at least 23
hostages, an army spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the attackers, suspected as members of the
outlawed Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), stormed
into the Guatape plant just after nightfall.
</P>
<P>
The power supply to the nearby industrial hub of Medellin and
Antioquia province was affected after the guerrillas disconnected
the main turbines in the plant.
</P>
<P>
Authorities there had to draw energy from smaller generators in
the area to fill the power gap caused by the attack.
</P>
<P>
The army has sent in helicopters to the area to help monitor
the situation and provide support to government troops in an event
of army operation.
</P>
<P>
The hostage-takers were still holed up in the plant at 10:30
p.m. local time (0330 GMT), the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The army has not decided what to do next, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
