<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Cases Drastically Drop in Dar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Cholera cases in the
Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam have dropped drastically from
more than 100 patients per day in April to only 16 by Wednesday,
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Cholera camps in Dar es Salaam are almost empty, some of them
have been closed and the rest have been left open to serve some
patients arriving from up-country.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Dar es Salaam City Commission Health Officer
Charles Kubenga as saying that the disease is disappearing in the
city as most of the recent cases were only imported.
</P>
<P>
Kubenga said that most people are now aware of the disease and
are observing hygienic rules such as boiling drinking water.
</P>
<P>
"This is a big city. We do not want to be caught unware,
because every day people, some of whom have already contracted
the disease, enter the city," Kubenga said.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned that the disease is still prevalent among the
population and there is a need to seriously adhere to hygienic
regulations so as to make its existence only a history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Teachers to Go on Strike over Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- About 240,000 teachers around
Kenya will go on strike on October 1 if the government fails to
meet their salary hike demands within 28 days, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya National Union of Teachers (KNUT) sent the strike
threat to Minister for Labor and Manpower Development Philip
Masinde Wednesday following a crisis meeting of the KNUT national
executive council.
</P>
<P>
The union is demanding a salary increase ranging between 150
and 200 percent as recommended by the remunerations committee,
instead of 10-to-28 percent announced by Education Minister
Joseph Kamotho Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The teachers have resolved that they will not accept anything
sort of the full implementation of the recommendations" made by
the committee, said KNUT Secretary-General Ambrose Adongo
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the recommendations, the lowly paid teacher
should get a minimum of 5,640 Shillings a month, with a top bar
of 7,079 Shillings. The highest paid teacher (chief principal) is
to get a minimum of 42,240 Shillings, with a top bar of 52,246
Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Currently around 62 Shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The remunerations committee also recommended automatic house
allowance for all cadre of teachers, with the lowest being 4,700
Shillings a month up from 640 Shillings. A chief principal is to
get 35,200 Shillings a month, up from 8,700 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Others are motor vehicle, transfer, hardship, commuter and
accommodation allowances.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, under the Kamotho's announcement, the lowest paid
teacher will start at 2,405 Shillings a month, up from 1,880
Shillings. The highest starts at 21,000 up from 19,115 Shillings,
with a ceiling 25,840 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The KNUT has described Kamotho's package as an insult to the
teachers in charge of about seven million children in the
country's primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kamotho argued that the government is unable to
give the hefty pay rise and lucrative benefits the committee had
recommended because of inadequate budgetary allocations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief Executive Ends Malaysian Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa left
here this afternoon for Singapore, the second leg of his first
overseas trip, after a two-day visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During his visit here, Tung had separate meetings with
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad and Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim to brief the Malaysian leaders on the
smooth transition of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR chief executive also had talks with Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi and Transport Minister Ling Lion
Sik.
</P>
<P>
He attended a reception at the Chinese Embassy in Malaysia in
his honor during which he told foreign dignitaries and guests that
July 1, 1997, was a very special day for everyone in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"It was a day which filled our hearts with pride and
confidence," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung delivered an address on "Hong Kong After the Transition"
at a luncheon here today organized by Malaysia's Asian Strategy
and Leadership Institute (ASLI) which was attended by some 500
people.
</P>
<P>
Tung told the attendants that since July 1, all branches of his
government in Hong Kong -- the executive, the legislature and the
judiciary -- have been functioning normally, there have been no
changes in lifestyle to which Hong Kong people have become
accustomed and economy continues to forge ahead.
</P>
<P>
This was the first overseas trip by Tung since assuming office
after China resumed the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on
July 1, 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
