<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Strives to Become International Clean City (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The east China port city of
Xiamen has concentrated its efforts on becoming one of the world's
cleanest cities.
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to fulfill the goal, Xiamen will allocate
some three percent of its gross domestic product (GDP) on
environmental protection during the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
The city, one of China's five special economic zones, has
achieved remarkable progress in pollution control, and has led the
nation's 13 pilot cities offering weekly air quality reports.
</P>
<P>
The city's forest coverage rate hit 34.3
percent in 1996, and its per-capita green area stands at
9.56 sq.m..
</P>
<P>
"I hardly recognize the city," said a tourist from Beijing who
first visited Xiamen in the early 1980s. He specifically cited the
foul odor from Yuandong Lake which previously permeated the
city.
</P>
<P>
This time, however, he expressed admiration for the park which
now surrounds the lake.
</P>
<P>
Tourists and local residents alike are highly satisfied with
the city's current environmental quality, with a recent random
sample survey indicating a satisfaction rate of 99.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We will never sacrifice the environment for the sake of
economic growth," said Mayor Hong Yongshi. The mayor's view is not
only the common view of the city's policymakers, but also that of
all residents.
</P>
<P>
Since the earliest periods of the city's opening to the
outside, the city has made it perfectly clear that no projects
creating heavy pollution will be allowed in Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
The city introduced its first local environmental regulation --
the "Xiamen Environmental Protection Regulation" -- shortly after
the National People's Congress granted local legislative
power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Strives to Become International Clean City (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The city's generous environmental investments are rarely seen
in the country. Between 1991-1995 alone, Xianen's spending on
environmental protection accounted for 1.5 percent of its total GDP,
an amount far above the national average of around 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The city's rapid growth over the past few years is directly
related to good environment," according to the mayor, who
expressed his belief that a good environment represents wealth
which can be used to create even more wealth.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen's beautiful environment, fresh air and improved urban
infrastructure facilities have attracted a vast array of overseas
hi-tech projects. The city had approved the use of nearly 12.8
billion US dollars in foreign funds by the end of last June,
and had approved the establishment of more than 3,100
foreign-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
The influx of overseas investment has sparked the
steady growth of the city's economy, with an average annual growth
rate of 23.3 percent between 1994-1996.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen's per capita GDP hit 25,000 yuan (3,125 US dollars) last
year, a 33.3-fold rise on 1980. The city is currently listed as
one of the nation's top 10 cities in terms of overall
strength.
</P>
<P>
However, the city's environmental quality remains at
levels of the 1980s due to the pressures of rapid economic growth,
urban expansion and population growth. Nonetheless, the overall
environment has witnessed improvement rather than deterioration.
</P>
<P>
A recent assessment conducted by the National Environmental
Protection Agency indicates that the city leads the nation in
coordinating social, economic and environmental activities.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Xiamen is far from contented over its
achievements. Mayor Hong Yongshi vowed to transform Xiamen into a
modern international scenic port city with rapid and healthy
economic growth, a good environment and ecology, and healthy
residents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
