<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 06:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Floats About Idea on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai was quoted today as saying that he is ready to
discuss a pullout from South Lebanon in order to end the bloody
confrontation there.
</P>
<P>
Israel was prepared to negotiate a withdrawal from Jezzine,
an enclave controlled by Israel in the west of South Lebanon,
and reach a peace agreement with the Lebanese in a matter of
days, the English daily The Jerusalem Post quoted Mordechai as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"We need to pursue every possible path that could lead to an
agreement, directly or indirectly, in which there will be
security and we will be outside (of Lebanon.)
</P>
<P>
"In the short or the long range we need to arrive at a
situation where we will end the conflict between ourselves and
the Syrians," said Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the remarks following the tragic death
of five Israeli soldiers, who were killed in South Lebanon last
Thursday in a brushfire caused by heavy fighting with
anti-Israeli guerrilla forces. There have been a total of 17
Israeli soldiers killed in South Lebanon's conflicts so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor party praised Mordechai's statements
about the pullout from South Lebanon, saying he had adopted
Labor leader Ehud Barak's plan for withdrawing from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been bogged down in a bloody guerrilla war with
anti-Israeli Muslim fighters in South Lebanon since the
establishment of the so-called South Lebanon Security Zone in
1985.
</P>
<P>
The heavy casualties of Israeli soldiers in South Lebanon
have led many Israelis to question the need of maintaining a
security zone, which has in fact failed to bring security to
Israel and continued increasing the death toll of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman met Wednesday with
representatives of two groups of parents of soldiers in Lebanon
who are demanding for a withdrawal from South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that he, too, had no patience for the ongoing
conflagration there, but that there was no alternative but to
remain in the security zone until a political solution was
found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
