<HEADLINE> South China Province Starts China's First BOT Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Construction of Laibin B Power
Plant of south China's Guangxi Province, the country's first
wholly foreign funded power project using the Build, Operate,
Transfer (BOT) investment practice, will begin tomorrow, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The consortium of Electricite de France (EDF) and GEC Alsthom,
which won the contract in an international bidding last year,
signed the final agreement here Wednesday with the government of
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua, EDF Chairman Edmond Alphandery
and GEC Alsthom Managing Director Nick Salmon attended the signing
ceremony of the contract.
</P>
<P>
Construction on the project, which will be equipped with two
360-megawatt thermal generating units, is expected to be completed
in the year 2000. The plant will be transferred to the autonomous
regional government after 15 years of commercial operation by the
two firms.
</P>
<P>
Of the total investment which is estimated at more than 600
million US dollars, about 25 percent will be offered by the
consortium.
</P>
<P>
"The project will help satisfy the region's increasing demand
for power and reverse its excessive reliance on hydropower," said
Yuan Zhengzhong, vice-chairman of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
