<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Proposes Further Redeployments During </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has promised further redeployments in the West
Bank on condition of the Palestinians' agreeing to an immediate
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published in today's English newspaper The
Jerusalem Post, Netanyahu said that the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) should accept his proposal for the immediate start
of the final-status talks, instead of negotiating further interim
agreements.
</P>
<P>
But he added that he would not deal with the core issues, such
as Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees and final borders, during the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accords, these issues should be settled through
the final-status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also stressed that there could be no additional
pullbacks unless the Palestinian side fulfills their commitment
to eliminate the terrorist infrastructure in their midst and
round up the alleged terrorists whose names were submitted to
them by the Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to the Note for Record attached to the Hebron
redeployment agreement signed in January, Israel should have
carried out the first phase of further redeployment in the West
Bank before March 7 and the final redeployment before mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
The first redeployment has been postponed because the PNA
rejected Israel's unilaterally decided scope of pullout, which
was set at 9 percent, much less than the 30 percent envisioned by
the PNA.
</P>
<P>
In response to the question about the possibility of
establishing a Palestinian state, Netanyahu said no sovereign
Palestinian state should be created because it could forge
military alliances with Israel's hostile powers such as Iran and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the pending visit to the region by United States
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Netanyahu expressed the
hope that Albright's first Middle East trip would contribute to
improving the situation.
</P>
<P>
"The immediate thing we are looking for is Palestinian
fulfillment of the obligations to fight terrorism and dismantle
the terrorist infrastructure," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the prospect of peace talks with Syria, Netanyahu said he
was "encouraged" by the way Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
exercised crisis control and stopped the recent escalation of
warfare between Israeli troops and Hezbollah guerrilla forces in
South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, he dismissed as a non-starter Assad's demand that
Israel should evacuate the entire Golan Heights and withdraw to
the June 4, 1967 armistice lines.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also revealed that his most pressing concern was
Iran's rapid buildup of a ballistic missile capability, due to
what he called Russia's "unlimited and unrestricted" technological
assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
