<HEADLINE> E. African States Urged for Joint Research in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Executive Secretary of
the East African Cooperation (EAC) Francis Muthaura has urged
countries in the sub-region to start joint scientific research in
agriculture to improve farm yield.
</P>
<P>
The EAC boss made the appeal when he opened a two-day meeting
of the East African Coffee Cooperation in Arusha, northern
Tanzania Wednesday, according to a news dispatch reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
Muthaura said that the future economies of Kenya, Tanzania and
Uganda depend on the development and adoption of new technologies
to boost production and diversification.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "Competitiveness can only be sustained on the basis
of constant improvement and innovation of the existing capacities
and establishment of new ones as a result of research and
investment."
</P>
<P>
This is the challenge of the single market and investment area
which the EAC is committed to establish in the sub-region, said
Muthaura who maintained that joint research programs carried out
within the framework of regional integration will make research
cost-effective and for the control of animal diseases and pests
in particular.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meeting are from Ethiopia, Kenya, Tanzania
and Uganda. 
</P>
