<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taoist Holy Land Protected in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China is making great efforts in
protecting the culture on Wudang Mountain, the most important
Taoist holy land in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, the central government has allocated over 10
million yuan (1.2 million US dollars) to renovate temples on the
mountain and reinforce the buildings from flooding and storm
damage, sources said.
</P>
<P>
An archive has been formed to contain all the information about
tens of thousands of relics, which are overseen by 80 specialists.
</P>
<P>
There are now over 200 ancient temples and other buildings on
the mountain, with the oldest dating back the 7th century when the
first group of Taoists settled there.
</P>
<P>
The Ming Dynasty launched a massive renovation program in the
15th century to turn the place into an architectural showplace.
</P>
<P>
Taoism is China's only homegrown major religion, developed some
2,000 years ago by Lao Zi, who believed that "everything comes
from nothing."
</P>
<P>
The religion now has followers worldwide, and the Wudang
Mountain has been included on UNESCO's world cultural heritage
list.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 06:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Requests Emergency Funds From Donors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has stated that it faces severe financial problem
and requests the Western donor countries to increase their aids to
the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post today quoted PNA Deputy Minister of Planning
and International Cooperation Anis Al-Qaq as saying that funding
cutbacks and delays from the donor nations will cause an
indefinite delay of salaries due for August in the whole PNA
territory.
</P>
<P>
The funding crisis has resulted in the current tour of
Planning and International Cooperation Minister Nabil Shaath to
Western European nations to request emergency cash and reschedule
for pledged money to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The donor nations have been reducing their aid to the PNA. In
1995, the nations gave the PNA 400 million U.S. dollars but last
year they dispersed only 260 million U.S. dollars. The PNA had
received 60 million U.S. dollars out of 1.35 billion earmarked for
new and existing programs so far.
</P>
<P>
This cash crisis became acute after the July Jerusalem bombing
when Israel held back tax revenues meant for the PNA. The
following month, the U.S. congress held back aid as well.
</P>
<P>
Anis said the current financial crisis and the closure
imposed by Israel on PNA territories has led to severe
deterioration in the economic situation and standard of living,
and the most affected changes can be seen in hospitals and
schools.
</P>
<P>
It also has prompted a revision of the PNA's expected budget
deficit, set at 50 million U.S. dollars, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
