<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Performance of China's Listed Firms Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The overall performance of
China's listed companies improved in the first half of this year,
according to their published interim reports.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the calculated mean of the per share
earnings, net asset-profit ratio, and net asset value per share of
the 706 listed companies were 0.1504 yuan, 5.485 percent, and
2.602 yuan, respectively, for the first six months of the
year. All of the three indicators were a bit better than a year
ago, when there were only 433 listed companies.
</P>
<P>
The majority of companies on the top-ten board for the three
indices were listed within the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show that the three indices for companies
listed in Shenzhen were marginally better than for firms on the
Shanghai market.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Changhong, a major electrical appliance manufacturer,
led all the listed firms in terms of core business income and net
profit. Shenzhen Development Bank topped the list of total assets,
while Jiangsu Chunlan secured the first place for per share
earnings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Achievements Impressive: WB Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
Wolfensohn today said that China's economic progress in recent
years is very impressive.
</P>
<P>
During a round-table conference with journalists from
Australia, China, India, Japan and the United States, Wolfensohn
said that the bank has carried out over 130 projects in China,
which are remarkable.
</P>
<P>
The bank has a terrific experience in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank chief dismissed Harry Wu's criticism on the
bank-supported projects in China.
</P>
<P>
"I sent out team over there and we covered every inch of where
it was we were, and Harry Wu, despite my request, has never come
to me with any evidence. He has never met with me about it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank's objective is to reduce poverty and sustain
stability and growth in the world. The bank will hold its 1997
annual meeting and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in Hong
Kong, China, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said that East and South Asia account for 60 percent of
the world's population while the poor in the region account for
over 70 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
But East Asia has demonstrated "tremendous growth over the last
years," close to 10 percent compounded growth, while South Asia
grew by some 4 or 5 percent during the period, Wolfensohn said,
adding that South Asia is catching up now, could reach around 7
percent in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
He noted that East Asia has now got 30 percent of the world's
total exports, becoming a major trading power in the world
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
