<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Continues to Fall Despite Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee, pegged to
the U.S. dollar, continues to weaken despite interventions by the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) during the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Indian currency continues to be under pressure to further
depreciate because of sustained demand for the dollar from
companies and importers, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Though the RBI intervened in both the spot and forward markets,
the Indian currency was quoted at 36.51 rupees per dollar at the
end of trading on Wednesday against Tuesday's close of 36.45
rupees a dollar.
</P>
<P>
The RBI has pumped 400 million to 500 million dollars into the
foreign exchange market in the last fortnight in a bid to arrest
the volatility and keep the rupee from falling steeply against the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
Changing its strategy, the RBI, which had been a net buyer of
dollars, started selling dollars in mid-August when the rupee
plunged from 35.7 to 36.14 rupees per dollar overnight.
</P>
<P>
Despite the central bank intervention, however, the rupee has
been steadily going down since then.
</P>
<P>
Dealers believe that the downslide of the rupee will continue
for some time as the government decision to hike prices of
petroleum products earlier this week will have a negative impact
on the currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dengue Alarm Sounds Again in Indian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian National
Institute of Communicable Diseases (NICD) has directed the civic
authorities to take immediate preventive measures to check the
spread of dengue diseases after two cases were reported here in
the Indian capital.
</P>
<P>
According to local media reports today, the directive was given
on Wednesday after a team of NICD officials, who treated the two
patients admitted to a private hospital here, found them
dengue-positive.
</P>
<P>
The NICD also found an increase in aedes mosquitoes, the main
transmitter of dengue viruses, in certain areas of the capital and
directed the civic authorities to keep a close watch on the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The dreaded disease became an epidemic in New Delhi last year,
claiming around 300 lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
