<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large U.S. Bank Seeks Business Opportunities in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- First Union Corporation,
the sixth largest bank holding company in the United States, is
seeking business opportunities in China, a senior bank official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Steven J. Bash, senior vice-president and managing director of
the First Union National Bank, told Chinese reporters that a
high-ranking bank delegation will visit China later this month to
assess the possibilities there.
</P>
<P>
The bank holding company, with assets of 143 billion U.S.
dollars and loans of 95 billion dollars plus deposits of 93
billion dollars, intends to establish partnerships with China on
the basis of mutual benefits, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will first provide services, the knowledge, the know-how
and even provide products to help them (Chinese banks) become more
efficient and more profitable," said Steven who is in charge of
the bank's International Financial Institutions.
</P>
<P>
The drive fell within the corporation's new strategy mapped out
late last year to expand its business scopes overseas. It has
opened offices in Hong Kong, Jakarta, Bombay, Johannesburg and
London and planned to set up more in Istanbul, Cairo and Sao
Paulo.
</P>
<P>
There have already been three or four U.S. banks operating in
China. Their success in establishing a foothold in fast growing
China may have prompted First Union to act more swiftly.
</P>
<P>
Steven detailed First Union's "China Strategy" as developing
joint programs with Chinese banks to increase common understanding
and to develop profitable business together, and providing
financial and advisory services to Chinese government ministries
as well as Chinese diplomatic missions worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The projected joint efforts include joint calling programs on
U.S. importers and exporters for U.S.-China directed trade
activity, building capital markets and trading partnerships,
offering training programs on a full range of financial products
and services and becoming a top letter of credit bank for the
Chinese banks.
</P>
<P>
The senior vice-president said his corporation was ready to
take the possible risks, believing it is the right time to take
action. However, he almost ruled out the immediate opening of a
branch in China.
</P>
<P>
"When making investment, we know it's long-term benefit," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
