<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Unity to Safeguard Asian Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar today called for unity
among Asian countries to safeguard the Asian interest.
</P>
<P>
In an editorial entitled "United Asia", official newspaper The
New Light of Myanmar said today that "more and more Asian nations
are becoming aware of the need for greater cohesion and
cooperation especially in the face of machinations on the part of
those who would like Asians to grow in a mould to their liking
which is not in the Asian interest."
</P>
<P>
"Those of us, who have suffered colonization under different
adventurers who exploited our natural resources and misguided the
people in line with their divide-and-rule, know all too well what
the former colonialists are up to by listening attentively to
their utterances," the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
"Values and interpretations differ. What we do cannot be gauged
by a yardstick that is prescribed in the west. With the end of the
Cold War, geopolitics emerges to the fore in areas hitherto
unknown," it added.
</P>
<P>
The editorial said that attempts to divide and destroy only
help Asians gain greater unity and cohesion for greater common
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
The editorial came in the wake of western criticisms of ASEAN's
admission of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar and Laos became full members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in July, which also embraces
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Myanmar's embassy in London issued a press release,
refuting British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook's recent remarks in
</P>
<P>
Singapore that Europe would oppose the participation of any
Myanmar representative in the second Asia-Europe Meeting scheduled
to be held in London next April for human rights and drug trade
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar said Cook's accusations were "unfounded,
uncharacteristic and discriminating."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
