<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Successful With Giant Panda External Artificial Insemination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully carried out the first external artificial
insemination experiment on a giant panda, taking a huge step
forward in the research on technological breeding of this
much-loved endangered species.
</P>
<P>
China has never before experimented with external fertilization
techniques on live giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
On August 4, researchers in Chengdu Panda Genetic and Embryo
Engineering Lab removed an ovary from a 17-year-old giant panda
who died from illness. Experts from two universities assisted.
</P>
<P>
They separated eggs from the ovary and fertilized them with
sperm after the maturation period.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also found many conjoined eggs in the panda ovary,
citing this as the reason for the high rate of panda twins.
</P>
<P>
The reproductive ability of the giant pandas is very low and
the area of their living space has reduced, and the number of
the giant pandas dropped sharply.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are only about 1,000 giant pandas remaining in
the wild in China.
</P>
<P>
Since 1953, Chinese and foreign zoos have raised a total of 132
female giant pandas. However, only 24 have given birth. Most of
female giant pandas remained childless their whole lives.
</P>
<P>
Experts here attributed the reason to cysts in the Fallopian
tubes which prevented regular ovulation.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Anju, a giant panda expert, said researchers will remove
ovum from the live pandas with the help of an abdominoscope. He
believed that in the near future, experts could use embryonal
biological engineering technology for the breeding of pandas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Hold Emergency Economic Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
hold an emergency economic summit Friday to review its strategy on
the national economy following the current "economic storm"
stirred up by high interest rates and a volatile foreign exchange
market.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo revealed that the decision
to hold a summit was reached during the Legislative-Executive
Development Advisory Council meeting at the Presidential Palace
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It was acknowledged during the meeting that "the wheels of
economic growth are slowing down," The Philippine Star today
quoted De Ocampo as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added the one-day economic summit, to be attended by
government economic managers and private sector business leaders,
was intended to "turn present difficulties into opportunities"
aside from setting policy directions.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo acknowledged that "the high interest regime may be
self-defeating," and must therefore be tackled. The economic
summit will also tackle a number of economic bills still pending
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
He said following a talk with Philippine Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson, there was an indication that the bank would
rethink its position on the higher interest rates, adding that the
economic summit should send a signal that the rates "should head
in the other direction."
</P>
<P>
As for the foreign exchange market volatility, De Ocampo
admitted that the government "must protect the exchange rate
against speculators, but at the same time must not unduly
interfere with the market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
