<HEADLINE> Milosevic, Bosnian Serb Leaders Meet on Serb Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic met Bosnian Serb leaders here Wednesday on the current
crisis in the Bosnian Serb Republic and further implementation of
the Dayton peace accords.
</P>
<P>
During talks with Serb member of the Bosnian Presidency Momcilo
Krajisnik, Bosnian Serb National Assembly Chairman Dragan Kalinic
and Bosnian Serb Government Prime Minister Gojko Klickovic,
Milosevic urged the Bosnian Serb members to actively participate
in the work of the federal government, the local newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Serb citizens and government should take an active part
in the coming local elections, which would help stablize the
current political situation, the Yugoslav president added.
</P>
<P>
The crisis among the Bosnian Serb leadership began in early
July, when Serb President Biljana Plavsic dissolved the parliament
despite strong opposition from it.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court ruled in August Plavsic's decision
unconstitutional, but met objection from Plavsic.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic also called on Serbs to show their confidence in the
people and agencies which would effectively protect Serb
republic's interests.
</P>
<P>
He believed that it is for their own good that the Serb people
firmly implement the Dayton peace accords signed in 1995 that
ended the three-and-a-half year civil war in Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
