<HEADLINE> China's Auto Production Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Competition among domestic
automakers is intensifying as more assembly plants are striving
for economies of scale, today's China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Late last month, the Changchun-based FAW-Volkswagen, a joint
venture between the First Automobile Corp (FAW) and Germany's
Volkswagen, passed State appraisal and evaluation for its 150,000
car project last month.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, the 8.9-billion-yuan project initiated in 1991 has
turned out 100,000 Jetta cars. Currently, it is manufacturing
150,000 cars, 270,000 engines and 180,000 transmissions annually.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, parts and components produced auto
parts locally equally 84.2 percent of the complete "Jetta" car. In
the first seven months of this year, the sales reached 44.75
million yuan after paying off loans and interests.
</P>
<P>
"The success of the project signaled a new era for the First
Automobile Corp, which has turned into a carmaker from a previous
truck manufacturer," said the appraisal statement.
</P>
<P>
Another joint project between FAW and Audi of Volkswagen, at an
investment of 1.87 billion yuan, is expected to produce 30,000
Audi 200s by 1998. Audi 200, a model similar to Audi V6, is a type
of state-of-the-art luxury sedan. To date, 2,000 Audi 200s have
rolled off the assembly line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
