<HEADLINE> Scotland to Change World Cup Qualifier to Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Scotland's World Cup qualifying
match against Belarus will be played on Sunday to prevent a clash
with the funeral of Princess Diana, the Scottish Football
Association suggested on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The match was scheduled originally on Saturday afternoon, hours
after the start of the funeral in London for princess Diana, who
was killed in a car crash in Paris last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
BBC Radio said the SFA had asked world soccer governing body
FIFA to allow the match to kick off at 1300 GMT on Sunday. And
both sides were reported to agree to the rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
Three key Scotland players, all from Glasgow Rangers, had said
they would not play if the match went ahead on Saturday while
politicians demanded action by the soccer authorities to change
the date.
</P>
<P>
Denis Law, a famous former player of Scotland, said playing the
match at the same time as the funeral could "tarnish Scotland's
image".
</P>
<P>
Scotland manager Craig Brown previously suggested a Friday
match because Belarus plays Austria next Wednesday and a Sunday
match would leave them too little time to recover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
