<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Investment Has Great Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Japanese officials
agreed Wednesday in Dalian, a port city in northeast China, that
there is a great potential to be tapped for Japanese investment in
China, today's China Daily said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese figures show new Japanese investment in the first half
of this year plunged 60.42 percent to 1.21 billion US dollars
compared to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
One reason for the decrease is China's decision to cancel
favorable tariffs on imported equipment for foreign-funded
companies. But a grace period is in place until the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investors began slowing their investments in China in
1996, and this trend has not changed yet, said Ikeura Kisaburo,
Director of the Japan-China Investment Promotion Organization.
</P>
<P>
"But I believe the potential is there...and is yet to be fully
tapped," he told a conference held by his organization and its
Chinese counterpart.
</P>
<P>
Now Japan is the largest foreign investor in China. Only Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan, all part of China, have bigger investments
in the Chinese interior.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yi, Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation,
indicated in her speech that a final cancellation of favorable
tariffs for foreign investors should not hinder foreign
investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Liquor Claims 54 Lives in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Illegal liquor claimed the
lives of 54 people by Tuesday and about 200 others seriously fell
ill after drinking the liquor in Batticaloa district of Eastern
province, Sri Lanka, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The 54 died after drinking liquor purchased from a private
distillery and distributed through both legal and illegal liquor
shops.
</P>
<P>
Police were probing into reports that a high concentration of
poisonous substance had been introduced into the Arrack, a popular
local brew, in a distillery either in Batticaloa or in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebels are suspected by Colombo police to have poisoned
the liquor, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said they suspected rebel involvement because on
an earlier occasion the rebels had removed several stocks from
these same liquor shops and issued contaminated Arrack.
</P>
<P>
Two persons have already been arrested in this connection and
204 bottles of the liquor were confiscated. All liquor shops in
the area have been closed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
