<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Leaves for Beijing on Official Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto left here today for a four-day official visit to China
aimed at further developing bilateral ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is the first Japanese prime minister to visit China
since former Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama visited the country
in May 1995.
</P>
<P>
Before the visit, Hashimoto outlined his diplomatic policy with
China in a speech that seeks to improve bilateral relations
through mutual understanding and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The trip, which marks the 25th anniversary of the normalization
of diplomatic relations between China and Japan, will take
Hashimoto to Beijing and two northeastern cities of Shenyang and
Dalian.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is expected to hold talks with Chinese Premier Li
Peng later on Thursday and meet Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
other Chinese leaders on Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, he will fly to Shenyang to visit a museum
memorializing the Manchurian Incident and then make an inspection
tour of an economic and technological development zone in Dalian
before returning to Japan on Sunday. 
</P>
