<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Stocks Gain Ground, Rupiah Stable on New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's stock prices
gained ground Wednesday and the rupiah stabilized following a
government announcement on plans to lift foreign portfolio
ownership limits and gradually decrease interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Stockbrokers said today share prices on the Jakarta Stock
Exchange rose 7 percent Wednesday, the first rise since August 27,
with the composite index jumping 33.57 points to close at 512.58.
</P>
<P>
The stock market lost 31 percent from its peak level on July 8
when the composite index reached 740.88 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said Wednesday's largest intra-day increase since July
8 was in response to the government's reform package announcement.
</P>
<P>
The government Wednesday announced a series of restructuring
measures aimed at enforcing economic stability following the
rupiah's depreciation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said Wednesday the government
will revise its budget, liberalize foreign purchase of shares,
strengthen the banking industry and raise the luxury sales tax on
several goods.
</P>
<P>
Most securities analysts agreed the government's planned
measures would help enliven investors' confidence in the country's
capital market, but that would not be enough.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's announcement also helped prevent the rupiah from
further falling against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Spot rupiah, which opened at 3,000/3,040 against the dollar,
dropped to a day low of 3,070 but soon recovered following the
announcement to close at 3,025/3,045.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said trading was slow and volume was thin throughout
the day, with the rupiah continuing to suffer from sustained
weakness in the region.
</P>
<P>
They said a strong recovery in the stock market might have
improved sentiment, but further falls in the Thai bath and the
Malaysian ringgit kept the rupiah below the 3,000 level.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rupiah, like other regional currencies, has come
under fierce speculative attacks following de factor devaluation
of the Thai bath and the Philippine peso in July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
