<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The front page praises a primary school headmaster who
devoted his life to the education cause in a mountainous
hinterland in west China's Qinghai province.
</P>
<P>
-- The paper carries a story on national unity and economic
development of ethnic minorities in the country over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
-- The State Council yesterday urged a minimum living standard
system be established in every city across the country by the end
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China has successfully wound up an experiment recently in
which a robot was sent 6000 meters deep into the Pacific to
study topography and mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
-- China's last issuing of listed treasury bonds this year,
which totals 13 billion yuan worth of 10-year-term T-bonds with an
annual interest rate of 9.78 percent, will make its debut on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
-- A number of 28 people from China's interior areas and Taiwan
yesterday participated in a long-distance running from Taibei
to Beijing with the theme of "run for the health of the Chinese".
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A national conference aimed at promoting the implementation
of Provisional Rules on the Handling of Personnel Disputes,
China's first such statute regarding disputes in government
institutions and state firms, will open in Nanjing, Jiangsu
province, in a week's time.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng expressed satisfaction with the
productive co-operation between China and Pakistan on bilateral
issues and international affairs, during his meeting with visiting
Pakistan Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Scientists are preserving and cataloguing more than 170,000
bamboo slips and wooden tablets, a historic discovery made last
October in downtown Changsha, central China's Hunan province,
</P>
