<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Remains Ideal Place for Overseas Investment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China remains one of the
favorite places for overseas investment, in spite of the fact that
the influx of foreign funds has slowed down this year, economists
here said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China had approved more than 290,000
overseas-funded businesses by the end of June, which have actually
used a total of 197.9 billion US dollars. Nearly 140,000
of the firms are already in operation and doing well, employing
some 17 million workers.
</P>
<P>
For four years China has ranked second in the world for using
overseas investment, next to the United States. By now, more than
200 of the world's top 500 multinational corporations have opened
business in China.
</P>
<P>
China will expand the areas and scale for overseas investment,
following the principle of "using overseas investment actively,
rationally and effectively," said Shi Guangsheng, vice-minister of
the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (Moftec).
</P>
<P>
Direct investment, loans, investment in securities, and other
forms of investment in China from the rest of the world have
added up to 300 billion US dollars. And China has become one of
the world's most attractive investment markets, Shi said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20 years of reform and opening up have brought the
potential China market into a reality. The Asian-Pacific region is
the fastest-growing economy in the world, whereas China, a major
contributor to this phenomenon, has made itself a hot spot for
overseas investment in the process.
</P>
<P>
A recent World Bank report estimated that China would need 280
billion US dollars in the next five years for its infrastructure,
much of which would be foreign funds. This shows that China will
be the world's largest infrastructure investment market.
</P>
<P>
China is seeking overseas financing for its infrastructure
projects, such as the Three Gorges Dam and the Beijing-Shanghai
Expressway which alone will require more than 10 billion US
dollars, according to the State Planning Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
