<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar to Set Up Drug Information Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Myanmar will soon
set up a coordinating center in the northern Thai city of Chiang
Mai to help wipe out border narcotics trade, it is learned here
today.
</P>
<P>
The center will be responsible for coordinating with concerned
agencies of the two countries to provide information about drug
trade and to map out suppression and prevention measures.
</P>
<P>
The center is being set up in accordance with an agreement
signed last week between the two countries on drug suppression
along their borders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Remains Ideal Place for Overseas Investment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 1.2 billion population itself offers a great consumer
market, while the improving living standards will further increase
people's purchasing power, thus opening more opportunities for
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
China this year began to shift to a quality vs. quantity
strategy in using overseas capital. As a result, the number of
newly approved solely foreign owned businesses exceeded that of
Sino-overseas joint ventures, and the number of large and key
projects approved by the State Council was on the rise.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, the amount of contractual
overseas investment went down on a year-on-year basis, but the
volume of overseas investment actually used still increased
by 1.49 percent.
</P>
<P>
China's readjustment on tax policies for overseas-funded
enterprises affected the flow of foreign capital. But most
importantly, China has been taking steps to boost the use of
overseas investment to a higher level to meet the needs of its
industrial improvement, at a time when the country is undergoing a
transition in the mode of economic growth from extensive to
intensive, explained Ma Xiuhong, a Moftec official.
</P>
<P>
China's macro-economic performance has entered the best period
of high increase and low inflation since the 1990s. Its exports
are reporting good records, with foreign currency reserves
topping 120 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that China's market advantages also lie in an improved
legal system which is to guarantee fair competition. More than
20 provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities have adopted
policies and regulations to protect the rights and interests of
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Statistics Bureau, more than half the
world's multinational firms have listed China as their first
choice for investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
