<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Prosecutors Seek Arrest of Former Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Anti-corruption investigators
from Milan today filed a request with the Justice Ministry for
authorization to arrest former defense minister Cesare Previti on
corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
Previti, a top Roma lawyer and close friend of media baron
Silvio Berlusconi, held the defense portfolio in Berlusconi's
government in May-December, 1994. He is the most senior serving
politician to face arrest since prosecutors moved on the then
Health Minister Francesco De Lorenzo in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The former defense minister said in a statement that he had
committed no crime and should not be arrested.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no justification for the request," said
Previti.
</P>
<P>
Under Italian law, magistrates must make a formal request to
parliament if they want to take a member into custody. "The
ministry's only role is to forward the authorization request to
the appropriate chamber immediately," a Justice Ministry official
said.
</P>
<P>
Ignazio La Russa, chairman of the parliamentary commission that
will initially examine the arrest request, said it would take
between seven and 10 days to study the matter.
</P>
<P>
The full lower house of parliament will then have to vote on
the commission's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports said the Milanese magistrates are charging
Previti with the corruption of an ex-judge, 71-year-old Renato
Squillante, formerly head of the preliminary investigations
magistrates in Rome.
</P>
<P>
Squillante allegedly accepted bribes to fix sentences,
especially in the IMI-Rovelli case in which the Rovelli family
allegedly paid 42 million U.S. dollars to fix the outcome of a
marathon civil case in which the late oil magnate, Nino Rovelli,
was suing the investment bank IMI (Istitito Mobiliare Italiano).
</P>
<P>
The funds were allegedly paid over to Previti, a lawyer for
Berlusconi's Fininvest empire, another Fininvest lawyer, Giovanni
Acampora, and civil lawyer Attilio Pacfiico.
</P>
<P>
Magistrates were told by one of the sons, Felice Rovelli, that
he paid the three lawyers on the express death-bed wishes of his
father, who died in 1990. Milan's "Clean Hands" prosecutors,
however, are reportedly convinced the heir played an active role
in the episode of corruption and was not merely carrying out his
father's wishes.
</P>
<P>
On May 17 last year, Acampora was arrested under a warrant
issued by prosecutors investigating Squillante in another case in
which he is accused of taking bribes to fix sentences in favor of
Fininvest.
</P>
<P>
Squillante was arrested on March 12 last year on orders of
Milan Clean Hands prosecutors and charged with corruption after a
witness told investigators the judge had taken bribes to fix
sentences.
</P>
<P>
Those bribes were reportedly paid by the civil attorney,
Pacifico, who was arrested, released to house arrest and then hit
by another arrest warrant on May 17, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The case in question started in 1982 and had not been settled
when Nino Rovelli died in 1990. It went to the supreme Cassation
Court twice and to the Constitutional Court, and at a key moment
an important file disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The case was finally settled in favor of Nino Rovelli's wife
and children, who lived in Switzerland, for a total of 980.2
billion lire (now 587 million U.S. dollars), including interest on
the original sum and legal costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
