<HEADLINE> China to Dam Yangtze at Three Gorges in November (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 4 (Xinhua) -- China will lock the main
stream of the Yangtze River at the Three Gorges in early November,
announced Lu Youmei, general manager of China Yangtze Three Gorges
Project Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
"Normally, the damming a river might be done in a dry season,
which falls between late January and late February each year, with
reduced water flow and drop that helps to alleviate the difficulty
of locking," said Lu, also deputy head of Three Gorges Project
Construction Committee under the State Council, the country's
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
"But to lock the Yangtze at the Three Gorges, it is necessary
not only to take water flow and drop into account, but also to
remember that after the locking, there should be enough time to
build two cofferdams to required heights before next May, when the
flood season of 1998 begins," Lu stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise, it would have catastrophic consequences on the
construction of the entire Three Gorges Dam Project," Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project, which began in December of 1994, is
situated on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River and is a major
part of China's effort to develop its longest river.
</P>
<P>
It will help prevent flooding along the Yangtze, and its
annual power output will reach 84.7 billion kwh. The entire
Three Gorges water control dam project will take 17 years to
complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mechanism Underlying "Mad Cow" Disease Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Researchers studying the human
form of the "mad cow" disease said they have found out how it
travels through the body and replicates before attacking the
brain, which could be the first step to give "mad cow" disease its
scientific name, ANSA reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Italian researcher, Adriano Aguzzi, together with other
scientists in his team at Zurich University's Institute of
Neuropathology said the discovery could help find effective
treatment for Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, the human disorder linked
to the BSE, or bovine spongiform encephalography.
</P>
<P>
"It's early to draw conclusions," Aguzzi said, "and we don't
know whether we'll find a cure for this disease, but we now have a
clear idea of what we are looking for."
</P>
<P>
His research was carried out on mice infected with scrapies,
the sheep's equivalent of the BSE or Creutzfeldt-Jakob.
</P>
<P>
Aguzzi and his team followed the anomalous prions (proteins)
believed to cause "mad cow" from the stomach to the spleen and the
lymphatic system. As a result, they found out that "mad cow"
replicate multiply with the help of normal prions once they reach
these two sites, building up sufficient numbers to attack the
brain in force through the peripheral nervous system.
</P>
<P>
Since the abnormal proteins called prions cause irreversible
damage when they hit the brain, so the treatment for "mad cow"
could involve stopping prions from multiplying in the peripheral
nervous system, according to Aguzzi.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of "mad cow" disease in Britain led to a major
crisis in EU relations over restrictions on exports of suspected
British beef, and the measures to be taken to curb the disease.
</P>
<P>
To halt the spread of the BSE, Britain has banned beef sales
and agreed to slaughter over 120,000 suspected heads of cattle.
</P>
<P>
The "mad cow" disease, which struck most heavily in England,
has appeared sporadically in the rest of the British Isles and
elsewhere in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Dam Yangtze at Three Gorges in November (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chinese engineers who initially set the time for damming the
Yangtze River in late November and early December also supported
the rescheduling of the work for early November, saying this will
give construction workers plenty of time to finish the required
building before the start of 1998's flood season.
</P>
<P>
The locking of the river will signal the end of the first stage
construction. The second stage can be described as building two
cofferdams to cut the flow of the main stream of the Yangtze and
make way for workers to construct the main dam and workshops for
generators in between the two cofferdams.
</P>
<P>
According to the design requirements for the second stage of
construction, the cofferdams must be 76 m high and use a total of
11.3 million cu m of earth, and an anti-leak embankment must be
built covering an area of 730,000 sq m before the flood season of
1998.
</P>
<P>
A number of conditions have made it possible to carry out the
locking ahead of the schedule, said Lu Youmei.
</P>
<P>
For the past ten years, Chinese experts who have studied daily
analysis of the water flow from October to December near the dam
site have concluded that water discharge in the area allow for an
earlier damming of the river.
</P>
<P>
The experts also have solved a range of difficult technical
problems related to locking through many years' research,
also making it possible for an earlier damming.
</P>
<P>
A canal designed for use after the damming has helped divert
water from the Yangtze since May and will be open for navigation
in October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mao's Fellow Villagers Better Off Under Market-Oriented Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- In a faded photograph taken
over 30 years ago, Tang Ruiren, barefooted and in shabby clothes,
smiled shyly beside China's late Chairman Mao, who was visiting
Shaoshan village, his hometown in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The former poor woman of Chairman Mao's native place has now
become the owner of a successful restaurant, named "Mao's
Restaurant" in honor of the founder of new China, and donates over
500,000 yuan (60,000 US dollars) to public welfare services
each year.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to Chairman Mao, I was liberated. Thanks to Deng
Xiaoping, I have become rich," said 67-year-old Tang Ruiren,
wearing a fashionable silk dress and a gold locket bearing Mao's
likeness.
</P>
<P>
Tang is not the only villager from Mao's hometown to benefit
from the market-oriented policies.
</P>
<P>
"There were very few self-employed laborers in the late 1970s
but now more than half the villagers are doing business," said
Wang Zhisen, a peddler selling tourist souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
Wang, together with her husband, head of the village's
construction team, are earning over tens of thousands of yuan
every year.
</P>
<P>
The total income of Shaoshan village exceeded 100 million yuan
(12 million US dollars) last year, compared to only 6,000
yuan (731 US dollars) in the early 1980s, according to
present village head Mao Shiyu.
</P>
<P>
"Every family in the village will have access to cable TV
services in the next two years, and 95 percent of them will have
telephones in their houses," Mao Shiyu added.
</P>
<P>
According to a local economist, the economic boom in the small
village is just "a miniature view of the whole province."
</P>
<P>
He said that during the past five years, Hunan had made
unprecedented progress in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of last year, he said, Hunan's GDP has kept
increasing by more than 12 percent, about two to three percentage
points higher than the country's GDP growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the province also show their confidence in Hunan's
economic prospects in the next century.
</P>
<P>
"The belt region along the Beijing-Guangzhou railway, including
Mao's hometown, is now emerging as a growth standard for the
entire province's economic take-off," said Wang Maolin, the
Secretary of Hunan Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of
China. chief of Hunan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
