<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Rusedski Reaches U.S. Open Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Greg Rusedski
stormed past former Wimbledon champion Richard Krajicek of the
Netherlands in straight sets on Wednesday to reach the semifinals
at the U.S. Open tennis tourney in New York.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski, wearing a black ribbon in memory of Princess Diana,
won 7-5, 7-6, 7-6 in a fast-speed match. He became the first male
player from Britain to reach the U.S. Open semifinals since Mike
Sangster in 1961.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski had beaten Krajicek in four of five previous meetings
but had far less big match experience than the Dutchman.
</P>
<P>
"I'd never won a match here. All the hard work is finally
paying off," said Rusedski, who is ranked 20th in the world, two
places below Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
In the semifinals, Rusedski will face either unseeded Swede
Jonas Bjorkman, who has been playing the best tennis of his life,
or 15th-seeded Czech Petr Korda, who pulled off the biggest upset
of the tournament with his fourth-round shocker over four-time
champion Pete Sampras of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, sixth-seeded Lindsay Davenport of the United
States also claimed her first career Grand Slam semifinal berth,
beating her doubles partner, third seed Jana Novotna, 6-2, 4-6,
7-6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
