<HEADLINE> CIA Releases New Information About Missing Hondurans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA) has released new information on 187
Hondurans missing during the last decade`s civil war in Honduras,
the National Commission for Human Rights said today.
</P>
<P>
The CIA presented a 300-page document unleaking names who were
responsible for the missing people and delivered some clues,
Commission President Leo Valladares said.
</P>
<P>
He said as soon as the document is analyzed, he will turn it
over to the corresponding authorities.
</P>
<P>
Valladares urged the 13 former Honduran military officers who
were involved in the case to confess their crimes to the
country`s courts.
</P>
<P>
"They have claimed innocence, but if they are actually
innocent, they must prove it," Valladares said.
</P>
<P>
Catholic Priest James Carney`s relatives have asked the
government to find out what really happened in the clergy`s
disappearance in the mountains of Olancho in the northeast
department in 1982, when he served as a chaplain for a rebel
group, Valladares added. 
</P>
