<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Observe First Fair Play Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 3 (Xinhua) -- In a latest bid to boost the
flagging sportsmanship worldwide, the International Football
Federation (FIFA) has designated September 20-21 this year as the
first Fair Play Days.
</P>
<P>
FIFA Secretary General Joseph Blatter made the announcement at
a press conference here Wednesday on the eve of the 7th FIFA
Under-17 World Championship slated for Egypt from September 4-21.
</P>
<P>
The Fair Play Days will coincide with the final matches of the
U-17 event. A total of 16 teams from five continents will play 32
matches in four Egyptian cities during the competition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, FIFA's 192 members will stage a variety of
activities to attract the maximum attention to the theme of fair
play during these two days of September, the busiest month for
footballers all over the world, according to Blatter.
</P>
<P>
On September 21, the "fairest team" participating in the U-17
championship will receive a 10,000-Swiss franc award and can
donate it to Egypt's branch of SOS Children's Village, a
FIFA-funded program established in Austria 15 years ago, said the
secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Keith Cooper, FIFA communications director, on his part,
praised highly of the visits to the children's homes paid by the
Austrian U-17 team in Alexandria on Wednesday and to be made by
the German team in Cairo next week.
</P>
<P>
"It is not easy for the 16- or 17-year-old boys to show such
concern (for this cause), a gesture that should be recognized," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Cooper criticized the overwhelming tendency
to seek fame and fortune while neglecting moral integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Teams now prefer to win cups and medals while they consider
fair play only secondary. It is even more difficult to encourage
media to support the principle of fair play," he lamented.
</P>
<P>
Recalling the last World Youth Championship (U-21) held in
June-July, the FIFA director said the youngsters played well in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"It was characterized by exceptional level of fair play as
well," he added.
</P>
<P>
He was very proud of the fact that only three red cards were
handed out during the 52 matches. "This perfectly demonstrated
that fair football is better than hot football," he said.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA secretary general chipped in, adding that U-17 World
Championships has so far had no doping tests failure and therefore
is "very clean." 
</P>
</TEXT>
