<HEADLINE> U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Visits Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kiev, September 3 (Xinhua) -- United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees Sadako Ogata Arrived here today for a three-day visit
to discuss further cooperation between Ukraine and the world body.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the airport upon her arrival, Ogata said that she
wanted to thank the Ukrainian government for its concern to
refugee problem and aid rendered to refugees in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian State Committee for Migration disclosed that
almost 5,000 people from members of Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) have applied for refugee status in Ukraine over the
past two years. Some 1,830 people including 740 children have
attained the refugee status.
</P>
<P>
One of Ukraine's biggest headaches is the problem of social
absorption and accommodation of the Crimean Tartar returnees
numbering about 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
During her visit, Ogata is scheduled to meet Ukrainian
President Leonid Kuchma, Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and
Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko.
</P>
<P>
She will also visit a school for Afghan refugees in Kiev and
some refugee centers on the Crimea Peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
