<HEADLINE> U.S. Might Consider More Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that it would consider more food aid to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) if the U.N. World Food Program
makes a fresh appeal for the famine-stricken country.
</P>
<P>
"We would be willing to look at any additional requests that
the World Food Program might bring our way," State Department
spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Foley made the remarks after press reports indicated that the
World Food Program might make a new appeal as it was making
assessment of damage by last month's typhoon-fueled tidal wave
that has smashed dikes and flooded fields in DPRK, destroying an
estimated 700,000 metric tons of corn.
</P>
<P>
The United States has shipped food assistance worth 52 million
U.S. dollars to DPRK this year in response to the World Food
Program's appeals. 
</P>
