<HEADLINE> Philippines to Lower 1997 Economic Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
revising its economic target for this year in the light of the
poor economic performance during the first half of the year, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is unlikely to attain its 7 percent economic
growth target this year due to the currency crisis and the
resulting high interest rates, Economic Planning Secretary Cielito
Habito was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Habito's comments came after the peso fell to an all-time low
of 31.83 pesos to the US dollar in trading on Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The high interest rates and the prevailing currency turmoil in
the Asian region have left the government no choice but to
reassess the country's growth target for the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Habito said the slowdown in economic growth in the first half
of 1997, which averaged 5.9 percent, left the economy the tough
act of expanding by at least 8.1 percent for the final half to
achieve the 7 percent target by the year's end.
</P>
<P>
He said while other sectors of the economy continued to grow,
important foreign exchange-based components, like withdrawals from
dollar reserves, the slowdown in the remittances from overseas
Filipino workers and lesser influx of foreign investments, have
contributed to a "slower performance" of the economic growth.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the worsening currency crisis, President Ramos
has called a meeting among government economic managers and
private sector business leaders to assess the country's economic
situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
