<HEADLINE> Maradona Tested Positive in Second Sample </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, September 3 (Xinhua) -- The second test on a
urine sample from Diego Maradona confirms that the soccer star
took drugs before a league game 10 days ago, the Argentine
Football Association announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
AFA spokesman Albino Bemposta said that Maradona had tested
positive for a prohibited substance, which was forbidden by law to
be revealed.
</P>
<P>
With the second test being postive, the 36-year-old Maradona is
almost certain his career with a lengthy playing ban and also
faces a trial at a federal court for use of a banned substance.
</P>
<P>
The second test was requested by Maradona, whose agent claims
the former Argentine captain may have been given a drink spiked
with drugs prior to Boca Juniors' August 24 victory over
Argentinos Juniors.
</P>
<P>
Maradona admits to being a cocaine addict. He recently
underwent extensive drug rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, he was banned after failing a drug test while playing
for Napoli in Italy. He was arrested in Buenos Aires that same
year and charged with cocaine possession and distribution.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 he was kicked out of the World Cup finals in the United
States after testing positive for what FIFA called a "cocktail" of
stimulants, including ephedrine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
