<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0045 GMT, September 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The Buckingham Palace announced here Wednesday that
the funeral procession route of Princess Diana would be extended
and begin from Diana's London home Kensington Palace.
</P>
<P>
The original procession route, which was from St James's Palace
to the Westminster Abbey, had been criticized as being too short.
</P>
<P>
A Buckingham Palace spokesman said that the procession plan was
changed because of safety considerations.
</P>
<P>
"We've always tried to consider a way of lengthening the route
in such a way that more people would be able to see the procession
in safety," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. mediator Dennis Ross held lengthy talks
Wednesday with an Israeli delegation ahead of Madeleine Albright's
first trip since she became the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
Ross and State Department officials avoided any description of
Ross's four-hour meeting with Israeli Cabinet secretary Danny
Naveh and Uzi Arad, foreign policy advisor to Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to take the Middle East trip next Tuesday
and will meet leaders of Israel, the Palestinian Authority, Egypt,
Jordan, Syria, Saudi Arabia and possibly Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley, replying reporters'
questions, declined to list the issues Ross and then Albright
would discuss with the Palestinians and Israelis. However, he
noted the security situation had improved since a twin suicide
bomb killed 17 people at a Jerusalem market on July 30.
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The baht plunged to an all-time low Wedensday on the
local market and selling prices at some leading commercial banks
on spot trading once exceeded 37 baht against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The selling price at Bangkok Bank today once hit 37.56 against
the dollar, while the baht was at one point sold at 37.65 to the
dollar at Krung Thai Bank.
</P>
<P>
Thai central bank governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi said that in
addition to the strong dollar, the psychological factor might also
 have fueled the baht slump.
</P>
<P>
He called on the public to remain calm.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Two Jewish young men were shot dead Wednesday near
Jerusalem and the Israeli police forces are hunting the suspects,
Israeli police said.
</P>
<P>
The police told the Israeli radio that the incident occurred
at about 3:00 pm (local time) on the road west of Givat Zeev,
which is about 10 kilometers northwest of Jerusalem. One of the
young men was shot dead inside the car and another was found
lying nearby.
</P>
<P>
The two were identified as young Jewish residents of Jerusalem
and the incident might be a criminal shooting because one of the
dead had criminal records in the past, police said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
