<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Offers Paradise For Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, September 4 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province,
home to several world-famous Chinese personages, including the
great educator and thinker Confucius, has extended great efforts
to become a paradise for tourists.
</P>
<P>
The province has improved tourism infrastructure by renovating,
expanding and constructing a large number of cultural, historic
and scenic sites.
</P>
<P>
Shandong has also introduced wide-ranging approaches for
allowing tourists to discover its abundant ancient sites, as well
as its mountain and coastal sceneries.
</P>
<P>
The province has also established a sound legal system to
protect the rights of tourists and businessmen involved in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
Shandong has introduced a number of festive events in recent
years to serve both the Chinese and people from abroad, with
regularly scheduled attractions including the Qufu International
Confucius Festival, the Weifang International Kite Festival, the
Qingdao International Beer Festival and Mount Tai Mountaineering
Festival.
</P>
<P>
Local governments in Shandong have dispatched numerous tourism
promotion teams to countries and regions throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that, the province hosted over 1.77 million
overseas tourists between 1992-1996, earning 595 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of foreign tourists visiting Shandong came from South
Korea, Singapore, the United States, Canada, Malaysia, the United
Kingdom and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Numerous tourists from throughout China have flocked to enjoy
Shandong's picturesque and historic sites. Some 51.15 million
domestic tourists visited Shandong in 1996 alone, with related
earnings hitting 18.74 billion yuan (2.28 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Shandong's tourism industry has an annual output of over 20
billion yuan, or 10.5 percent of the total for the province's
tertiary sector.
</P>
<P>
The province has 115 star-rated hotels and 238 travel agents,
as well as over 2,600 vehicles and vessels dedicated to
transporting tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
