<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suzhou Becomes Major Foreign Investment Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- Suzhou City, located near
Shanghai, China's largest industrial metropolis, has emerged as
the second largest foreign investment zone along the Yangtze
River, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou, a picturesque city in east China's Jiangsu Province,
has attracted foreign capital of over 10 billion US dollars, more
than 40 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
The city attracted four billion US dollars in foreign investment
annually between 1992-1996.
</P>
<P>
Suzhou used 2.2 billion US dollars foreign capital in 1996
alone, with the figure for the first half of this year jumping by
50 percent on the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The city is currently home to over 5,000 foreign-funded
enterprises, with investors from 79 countries and
regions and total contracted investment standing at 23.2 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-six of the world's 500 top international companies,
including Samsung, Panasonic, Toyota and Siemens, have established
ventures in Suzhou.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
