<HEADLINE> Beijing to Improve Management of Book Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital city will
issue new regulations to manage marketing of its books,
newspapers, periodicals and electronic publications, today's
"China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, which are bing discussed by Beijing's
law-makers, will ban people from buying and selling book and
periodical numbers, and producing and selling pornographic
publications and pirated materials, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
The regulations make it compulsory that firms release sample
publications to related media and publication departments for
examination, the paper adds.
</P>
<P>
During 1995 and 1996, more than 1.3 million illegal books and
periodicals and more than 500,000 pirated CDs were seized in
Beijing, according to the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
