<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Buicks to Be Available in China in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 4 (Xinhua) -- The first Buick sedan
manufactured in Shanghai city will be available on the Chinese
market late next year, according to a senior manager of the US's
GM.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai GM Co., a joint venture of Shanghai Automotive
Industry Corporation (SAIC) and GM that started last March, is
now preparing for production, said Robert Coletta, GM's
Vice President.
</P>
<P>
The local content ratio of the car will begin at 40 percent,
and the production capacity will eventually reach 100,000 units a
year, he said. The company's Buick sedan, he believes, will win a
certain part of the imported car market in China because GM's
investment was based on a thorough market survey.
</P>
<P>
The project is estimated at 1.57 billion US dollars and is the
largest Sino-US joint venture where each party has a fifty-percent
stake.
</P>
<P>
The two also put 50 million US dollars into the Pan Asia
Technical Automotive Center that will design and develop new car
models.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is China's leading auto producer. The
Shanghai-Volkswagen Automobile Co., a joint venture with Germany's
Volkswagen AG, is now China's largest passenger car manufacturer.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
