<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deep-Sea Robot Completes Pacific Exploration Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 4 (xinhua) -- China's first remote deep-sea
robot, capable of exploring at depths of 6,000 meters, recently
completed a seabed survey for polymetallic nodules in the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The successful application of the intelligent robot moves China
into the ranks of the world's few world countries with the
capability to produce advanced seabed survey instruments.
</P>
<P>
Feng Xisheng, director of the deep-sea robot project and a
researcher with the Shenyang Institute of Automation under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences, said Wednesday that the 39-day survey
proved that the robot is capable of completing designed survey
tasks.
</P>
<P>
He said the survey collected some 100 megabits of data and
videotapes of 10.8 sq.km. of ocean floor, and took 240
photographs.
</P>
<P>
The new remote robots, a cooperative Sino-Russian design,
provide more precise data and photo imaging than older robots
attached to cables. Feng noted that the remote robot has worked
for six successive hours at a depth of 5,217 meters.
</P>
<P>
The atmospheric pressure of 600 at a depth of 6,000 meters
create difficulty in spreading electromagnetic waves, the research
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Feng, the robot's capabilities include
videotaping, photography. geodetic surveying, polymetallic nodules
sampling, tracking of submerged targets and automatic recording
of data.
</P>
<P>
The robot is also capable of making automatic ascents when
encountering difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Feng said Chinese scientists are currently engaged in research
to enable the robot to conduct round-the-clock operations, and
will equip the robot mechanical appendages to for seabed
sampling.
</P>
<P>
Jia Peifa, director of the intelligent robot experts research
group, noted that seven units are conducting the deep-sea robot
project -- the CAS Shenyang Institute of Automation, CAS Institute
of Acoustics, the China Ship Research Center, Harbin Engineering
University, Shanghai Jiaotong University and two research
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The intelligent robot research program, one of the nation's
major high-tech projects, is being carried out at a cost of over
200 million yuan (24 million US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
