<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Performance Improves in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Due to strict macroeconomic
adjustment measures by Latin American nations in the past several
years, a firmer foundation for continued economic expansion has
been established in the region, a professional study shows.
</P>
<P>
These efforts have resulted in a reduction of the region's risk
profile and increasing investor confidence in many countries that
could lead to similar performance next year, the Miami-based Price
Waterhouse LLP Latin American Business Center said today.
</P>
<P>
However, the center said in its mid-year report on the economic
outlook for Latin America and the Caribbean that faster economic
growth continues to be hindered by macroeconomic imbalances as
well as inconsistent application of economic and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
Changing global economic and financial conditions over the
coming year could also impact the region's medium and long-term
prospects, said the report, adding that possible interest rate
increases in the industrialized countries may have an adverse
effect on the presently strong capital inflows into the region.
</P>
<P>
The center is part of a worldwide Price Waterhouse network of
economic services and information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
