<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firm to Help Explore Gold in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese company operating in
northern Nigeria said today it has signed a joint venture contract
with a local partner for gold exploration and exploitation.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, China Geo-Engineering Corporation (CGC) will
provide technical and consulting services for Blobemark Nigeria Ltd. in
gold prospecting and mining, CGC Deputy Managing Director Bi Deqi told
Xinhua over the phone.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Chinese company will joint hand with Globemark in
the exploitation of alluvial gold deposits in Edo state, southern
Nigeria, which is expected to begin before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The economic belt of the mineral stretches over 2,000 km in Edo
state, where alluvial gold deposits might be 200 kg or more.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese company also believes primary gold deposits could be
found in the area, and will provide technical know-how and part of
equipment in search of it, Bi said.
</P>
<P>
The two-year contract was signed Tuesday in Abjua, capital of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
CGC, based in north Nigeria's Kaduna state, has been operating in
the country for many years and its past business deals mainly cover
the sink of wells and other projects related to water supply.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time the Chinese company is engaged in mineral
exploration in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Globemark is Nigeria's first private-owned mining company engaged
in gold prospecting and exploitation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
