<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Accused of Breaching ECOWAS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today accused Sierra Leone's
military junta of violating a sub-regional resolution on the country
by planning to launch attack against the west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
According to a statement of the defense headquarters, the junta
leader Major Johnny Koroma today met information and unit commanders
in the capital Freetown to "work out strategies to launch an offensive
attack on ECOMOG troops".
</P>
<P>
"The planned attack on ECOMOG positions will be carried out
within 24 hours," said the statement, quoted by a Nigerian
television authority report.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG troops have remained on the defensive in compliance
with the summit of the Economic Community of West African Countries
which ended last week in the Nigerian capital of Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The 20th ECOWAS summit of heads of state and government resolved
that economic sanctions would be adopted, instead of war, against the
junta which overthrew Sierra Leone's legitimate government in a coup
on May 25.
</P>
<P>
"The decision of the rebels to attack ECOMOG troops is a violation
of the summit resolution," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were sent to Freetown in the wake of the coup.
Repeated clashes have been reported between the ECOMOG troops and soldiers
loyal to the junta.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional force still holds in Lungi international airport
near Freetown.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
