<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Aid Volunteers Leave for Niger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria said today that seven
Nigerians have left for Niger, the northern neighbor of the country, as
volunteers of the Technical Aids Corps (TAC).
</P>
<P>
The seven medical personnel are the first set for a Francophone
country since the introduction of the scheme 10 years ago, said an
official of the TAC Directorate.
</P>
<P>
The scheme is aimed to enable Nigerian professionals to serve in
needy countries at the expense of the Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the experience of the seven people, who
left Monday, will provide a model for the evaluation of the scheme
in Francophone countries.
</P>
<P>
Some other volunteers for Equatorial Guinea, Kenya and Gambia
will soon leave for their services after a brief orientation
course for them last week.
</P>
<P>
About 250 TAC volunteers were selected for participation in the
scheme this year from more than 15,000 applicants, most of them
medical personnel, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
