<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Sending Mediator to Cyprus for Peace Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. mediator Thomas Miller
is planning a two-week trip to Cyprus and Europe in search of a
settlement formula for the divided Mediterranean island, the State
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
"I think the dates are September 7 through September 20.... He
will be taking the temperature in the various capitals, then
reporting back," spokesman James Foley said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the United States was meshing its diplomacy with
that of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
U.N. envoy Diego Cordovez presided over talks between Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash in Switzerland in August. But the talks ended in failure
in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Miller plans to begin his two-week trip Sunday and make stops
in Ankara, Athens, Nicosia and a number of European countries to
consult with leaders of the visited countries for a peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Turkish troops invaded the Mediterranean island country in
1974, and the Turkish Cypriot minority declared a separate
republic that has been recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Miller will report to Richard Holbrooke, the retired American
diplomat who agreed to return to diplomacy part-time to try to
resolve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"He (Holbrooke) is keeping a close eye on the situation. He's
going to meet with Miller on his return and then they're going
to decide what steps the U.S. government may take," Foley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
