<DOCNO> XIE19970904.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghanaian Leader Calls on Africans for Full </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's Vice-President John Atta
Mills has called on Africans, who seemed to have entered a new foreign
tutelage, to strive for full freedom and independence from colonialism.
</P>
<P>
"Even our course as political entities and social beings seems to
be taken over by others," he said at a colloquium opening in Cape
Coast, Ghana Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We seem to be marooned in a frozen frame of history where the very
people who enslaved us, colonized us and exploited us are telling us
what to do in every sphere of our lives," he was quoted by the News
Agency of Nigeria as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the people in the continent have been fighting for
freedom and independence for over 40 years, Mills asked: "How long
more are we to wait to transform that freedom into social advancement?
into real independence?"
</P>
<P>
"If we continue to expect others to think and plan our fate, and
influence the direction in which we must go, then we will wait through
the next millennium and more," the vice-president warned.
</P>
<P>
He called on Africans to defy those who sought to marginalize them
and keep them under tutelage in any shape or form, saying that Africa
of the diaspora must be fully reunited with the Africa at home.
</P>
<P>
He also urged African leaders to work hard at uniting the continent
for the benefit of all.
</P>
<P>
The colloquium is part of the 10-day Third Pan-African Historical
Theater Festival, or PANAFEST '97, which opened in Cape Coast last
Saturday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
